animal.description:
This dog is being fostered in Dallas TX and must be adopted within the Dallas, North Central Texas or the southern Oklahoma area.

NAME:               Betsy
GENDER:          Female (Spayed)
AGE:                   About 3 years
WEIGHT:          About 6.5 pounds
DOGS/CATS:  Needs to be an only dog, Unknown with cats
CHILDREN:     Should be fine with older, mature children (10 and older)

Introducing adorable Betsy. This girl has a fun and sweet personality. We adore her, and think that you will too.

Betsy was found running lost in the Arlington TX area. She had no collar, no tags and no microchip. She had obviously been lost for awhile as she was thin, covered in dirt and had very long nails. The Arlington Animal Shelter kept her safe and patiently waited for her owner to come to find her. When no owners stepped up, they reached out to CRT to see if we could provide a safe landing space as she searched for a forever home. We were thrilled to say yes.

The longer Betsy is in our program, the more we think she would do best as an only dog.  While Betsy gets along with the other Chihuahua in her foster home, she wants it on her terms.  Betsy does like to be the “boss” and will occasionally let the other dog know that she wants to be in charge – LOL.  It is starting to cause friction.  So we are updating her bio to say maybe an only dog situation where she can bask in all the love would be best!  Betsy also loves toys of all kinds. She has a favorite stuffed animal that she will carry around the house. And oh how she loves balls. She LOVES to play catch and hopes that her humans will play fetch with her every day. Our photographer captured some great pictures of Betsy with her ball (see her complete bio and photo shoot on our CRT website for adorable pictures of this.)

Betsy is a loving girl who wants someone she can snuggle with and show her affection. Betsy is a bit shy when she first meets new people, but she warms up quickly. Betsy loves to snuggle with her humans. She is adorable in all aspects and wants to be your best friend! She loves to be in the same room you are in. Betsy especially enjoys being on your lap in the evenings as you relax together. When not on your lap, she has a favorite pillow in front of the fireplace that she is enjoying during these cooler days.

Betsy is super smart. She has learned to “sit”. She picked up on the routines in her foster home very quickly. She is an energetic dog that loves to play. We believe the ideal home for Betsy would be an energetic, active home that would play with her every day. She would be best as an only do (her amily will need to spend lots of time with her). There are no children in her foster home, but we believe she would be fine with older, mature children (10 and older). She will bark at sounds, but settles down quickly.

Betsy is about 3 years old. She weighs a perfect 6.5 pounds and is fully grown. Betsy is tan with white highlights. She has perky ears. She also has a shorter tail (we are not sure if she was born that way, or something happened along the way, but her tail is constantly wagging). Betsy adores people so much. She would be great for a work at home family as she could actively share love with you all day long!

Betsy is doing well on her potty training. She will go to the door to let you know she has to go out to potty. At night, she loves sleeping with her humans, and snuggling under the covers with them. Betsy does well on a leash and we believe she would enjoy short walks with her family.

Betsy is being fostered in the DFW (Texas) area. If this sweet girl sounds like the right fit for your home, our CRT adoption form can be found at: http://www.chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application/

Betsy is spayed, micro chipped, up-to-date on shots, HW negative and on heartworm prevention. She is ready to join a loving family – could that family be yours?

This dog is a CRT rescue. Reference checks, adoption contract and $270.63 adoption donation required ($250 adoption donation and $20.63 Texas Sales Tax). Note: as of 1-1-20, the Texas State Comptroller office is requiring all rescue groups to collect sales tax on adoptions, even though we are all 501c3. We are all fighting this, but for now, have been told it is non-negotiable.

As part of our mission to reduce the number of unwanted and sick dogs, we require that all current pets are spayed or neutered, current on vaccinations and taking heart worm prevention. Applications will not be considered if one or more of these requirements are not met.

After filling out an adoption application (found at http://www.chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application/), please email DFWCoordinator@chihuahua-rescue.com if you are interested in this dog. Please be sure to read about our adoption process and then fill out an adoption application before emailing the contact person.

animal.description:
Maverick is a 4 year old Pitbull who is currently waiting for his forever home. He is a bit timid at first but opens up quickly with lots of love and treats.

**Words from Maverick: woof!

"The names, Maverick!
People don't know it yet but I'm pretty pawsome. I've been at the shelter for a minute now and I see a lot of other dogs come and go, the ones that leave go somewhere called their forever homes that include lots of room to run, sleep on fluffy beds, treats, more time with the humans that give them lots of pets and hugs! I love hugs and pets a lot!
The humans at the shelter spend time with me, and I don't like it when they try and leave. I get kind of sad so I try following them...
They use to give me medicated baths because I use to have no hair on my rear! I was good for those and don't really need them now but my skin may flare up sometimes.
I know I'm not a bad dog...Just have some things I need to work on and figure out, like this word "sit" that these humans keep nagging me about when they hold those yummy treats... I keep barking for them to just give it to me but they just hold it there...what the hecks that about?!
I love the humans, but I haven't decided if I want any siblings when I go to a forever home, I see other dogs here all the time and some I have disagreements with while others its like whatever.... I see these things called cats up in a window looking down on me and I just have staring contest with them....they always win...I get distracted when I see a human or toys!
Anyway...I'm going to stay pawsitive that someday I'll find a forever home too because they sound so cool!

Love,
Maverick! ?

Chelsea is another one of the five dogs that was seized from the same property that Cowboy came from. She is a very sweet dog, but she is also not good with cats. She walks very well on a leash and will sit for treats.  HW-; 44lbs; 4 yrs old; 11/24; female; lab mix

Pretty in Pink!  Petite Chelsea is just as cute as cute gets!  This smaller framed bully mix is meek and quiet in her approach and gave me the once over as I hooked her up for a walk.   The good news for both of us is that in no time,  she was slowly sauntering out to our front play yard where we were greeted with a nice warm sun on what was a chilly winter day.  Chelsea is slow and steady and is never in any real rush.   Super polite and calm in meeting other dogs,  she did a wonderful job slowly sniffing and checking out both a male and female dog.  Once the sniffs were complete,  her interest in the pet was sated and she went on her way.  Chelsea is not a clingy/needy girl and does not ask for much.  Her big gifts for us today were small cracked little smiles of gratitude, an occasional sniff of our faces and hands and the always very steady wagging tail.  We really enjoyed Chelsea and so will you!!

animal.description:
Stark is a very special boy who will need a patient, special family. He has a laundry list of medical problems, the least of which is a need to put some meat on his bones. This is due to the fact he has ""mega esophagus"", meaning the tube that carries food and liquid between the mouth and stomach gets larger and loses its ability to move food into the stomach. Thankfully, Stark is not showing any clinical signs of this issue, meaning he does not regurgitate his food at this point. We do however used raised bowls to feed him and have him on a low fat, prescription diet that is good for dogs with this condition. 

While Stark is only 2 and a half years old... and he also has what is called ""myasthenia gravis"", his legs are showing a lot of improvement! He has slowly been able to start walking and even running without too many problems from his back legs. Stark is a wonderful boy who has a lot to give to a family who is willing to help him learn how to best enjoy life, despite the medical issues he has. 
The vet would like to set the goal of being able to eventually taper off his meds, however at this point in time, we cannot say for certain whether this will happen. The vet is extremely pleased with how well he responded to the medicine and does have high hopes that he will eventually be able to be weaned off it. Stark is going to be a lot of work for his family, but promises he will do his best to make it all worth it! 

Once Stark is comfortable with his people he is extremely loving, yet still independent enough to not need constant attention, while preferring to be near his people. He is pretty much house trained, despite the fact that none of his legs are working wonderfully. While with his foster, he has not needed crated and has not shown destructive tendencies. Frankly, Stark sleeps on the couch at night like a lump! He's a smart boy who has become a sit and shake pro! Stark loves other dogs and has been able to begin playing with his foster brother while his legs are learning to keep up with him! Stark gets a little too excited when getting treats sometimes (don't we all?), but once he is told ""easy"" remembers that he should still have some manners. Stark doesn't get too excited over toys, but he is starting to occasionally enjoy a good tennis ball. Stark is learning to walk on a leash, and while not animal or person reactive, is still learning basic leash manners. He is definitely a very special boy with some special needs that are totally worth the trouble.

Stark is microchipped, up to date on vaccines, and heartworm negative. Because of his condition, we are going to wait until he is more stable to neuter him. Stark's adoption fee is $150 and it will be in the contract that you must take him to be neutered at our vet in approximately 6 months to a year when he is ready. This will be schedule by us and paid for at our expense. If you think you could be the special family that Stark needs, you can submit an application for him at www.pawpatroldayton.com/adopt. 

**Please research both myasthenia gravis and mega esophagus prior to applying for this sweet boy to ensure you understand the care he will require.** All of our animals are vaccinated, micro-chipped and spayed/neutered before being adopted.

animal.description:
In June 2020, our Gorgeous Greta was found as a city stray in New York, and was transferred to the Brooklyn outpost of NYCACC. As time passed, Shelter staff ascertained that Greta was pregnant, and then her options for adoption fizzled. She sat in the shelter for almost 6 weeks during the summer of COVID, until we could transport her safely to our Connecticut Rescue.

The Rescue process is extremely upsetting to most dogs, and not the ideal scenario for whelping pups. Despite all the traumatic changes, Greta sailed through her intake process, making friends at every turn. Once she was released to us, she continued to show a delightful personality and balanced nature. She gave birth to 6 healthy puppies on July 27, 2020.


Greta was a first rate Mama, and now that she has fulfilled her responsibilities, she is ready to live her best life. Greta doesn't have the over-the-top energy that we see so often in other members of the Bully breeds. She has a relatively calm demeanor and is easy to handle on lead. She would be an excellent choice for a novice Bully owner.

Of course, Bullies are higher energy than most dog breeds, so even though Greta is calm for a Bully, she still needs sufficient exercise to be happy. She has a strong, yet nimble physique, but is slightly chunky at 65 pounds, and is working on a 10 pound weight loss. Her coat is short, manageable and easy to groom. Greta is mostly tan with a striking white tuxedo markings.

Greta loves the outdoors, and enjoys her walks even in the harsh weather. She would be an ideal walking companion, and would do well with one to two brisk leash walks each day, plus focussed playtime and obedience work. She has had a good deal of obedience training, and knows all her basic commands. She has begun her Canine Good Citizen program and impresses us every day. Adopters should continue her program, and develop her full potential. Bullies as loving as a Greta should be the Breed Ambassadors.

Greta could join just about any kind of active home. She is generally well behaved, and friendly to all. Although she is fairly easy to handle, she may overwhelm toddlers, but she'd be fine with older children and other well behaved dogs. We have not tested her with cats.

Greta has excellent house manners, and at the age of three, is well past the puppy mayhem stage. She is house trained and crate trained, although adopters should expect to troubleshoot the occasional accident that may occur as she adjusts to a new routine. Greta is a calm car passenger, and behaves well in public.

Greta has been spayed and vaccinated for routine shots. She has had a negative 4snap test, and has been microchipped and dewormed. If you are interested in Greta, please write to Denise at Angelsfrgod@aol.com or call Denise at 860-908-9738 for more info.

animal.description:
Name: Barry
Suspected Breed(s): Collie mix
Gender: Male
Age: 9 months old
Weight: 73.5 lbs
Personality: adaptable, loyal, playful, eager to please, quick learner, snuggler, smart, protective, trainable, friendly
Observations with Dogs: Barry needs training to properly greet other dogs when on walks. That said, he has fun and plays well with the resident dogs in his previous and current foster home.
Observations with Cats: Barry does well with cats.
Observations with Kids: Barry enjoys playing with the tweens in his foster home. He may be a bit much for a home with young children, as he may inadvertently knock a young child over while trying to show his love.
House Training Progress: No recent accidents. 
Crate Training Progress: Dislikes the crate, but is well-behaved in the home and is trusted to be left uncrated.
Location: DC area foster
Rescued From: Roane County, WV
Additional Information: Barry is a big, adorable lovebug at home. He is a pro at doing tricks for treats, and he already knows sit, shake, down, wait, and come. Barry also enjoys playing with his toys (he loves to chew!) and chasing the ball around. He has a lot of energy and would love an adopter with a big yard or who likes to go on runs or hikes! Barry is an extra-large puppy! He's affectionate and is still learning leash manners, so he needs an adopter who is willing to work on training to help him mature into the polite dog we know he can be. He gets along well with the resident dog at his foster home, but Barry is a big boy who gets over-excited when he encounters other dogs on walks. Speaking of excitement, Barry loves greeting new humans, and he is learning that jumping up is not the best way to show that joy.

In addition to being movie star handsome, Barry is well behaved in the house and very friendly and playful. He will talk to you like Chewbacca when he is excited about something like a walk or a meal, or just to tell you he loves you. (For this reason he may not be the best fit for an apartment building.) Barry is also a good watchdog; he'll let you know a package is delivered before the porch pirates have a chance. He loves kids and is playful with other dogs and seems fine with cats. Barry is BIG. If you love big dogs (and who doesn't?) he might be just the one for you.

Barry is sponsored by Kevin R. Thank you for saving a life!

__________________________________

If you are interested in meeting a dog or cat, we require an adoption application. If the animal has "HAS APPLICATION" listed, they are still available to receive additional applications but also may be in the process of being adopted soon. Apply for a DOG: http://www.citydogsrescuedc.org/adoptable-dogs.html

Interested in saving more lives? Foster a dog today! Learn more, see our list of dogs needing foster, and apply, https://www.citydogsrescuedc.org/foster-a-city-dog.html

City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is a foster-based rescue in Washington, DC. We do not have a shelter. We focus on local adoptions in DC and the metro area of Maryland and Virginia. CDR&CK has a thorough adoption process in order to find the best possible fit for each of our dogs and cats (we do not operate under a first-come, first served model).

Upon accepting a new cat or dog into the organization, we provide a basic vet visit that includes necessary vaccinations, disease screenings, deworming, microchips, and spay/neuter (unless specified). We do not provide a comprehensive medical exam prior to adoption. As a result, sickness, injury, and disability may exist unbeknownst to CDR&CK. City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is not responsible for payment of any vet care, including known and unknown medical conditions once a cat or dog is adopted from us. 
Dog specific: Rabies, DHPP, Bordatella vaccines. They are tested for HW, Lyme, Ehrlichia, Anaplasmosis.

Most cats and dogs will have a house training accident in the initial days in their new home and we cannot guarantee any pet is housebroken or crate trained.

We also update our Facebook page daily with new cats and dogs.

animal.description: Are you looking for a good boy? That's exactly what I'm trying to be! I will need someone that is able to give me lots of time to adjust and move slowly as I learn to be the best dog ever. I am used to being an independent, outside dog so I am still adjusting to the cushy, home life and will need some guidance. I really love being inside, but I haven't quite figured out how to be comfortable with constant companionship yet. I really prefer the company of adults to kids. I think of myself as a very mature guy and want to keep mature company. Because I have been so independent my whole life, I would be best as the only pet in the home. My biggest quirk is that I am a very social eater! I would love to have a spot at the dinner table next to you! If you are ready to have a dog that you can bond with over training, I'm exactly the guy for you! Come adopt me today.

animal.description:
Meet Mira! 

Mira is the perfect canine companion! This two-year old, 45# mixed-breed beauty, is a world-class snuggler and will crawl onto your lap at every opportunity. She likes to nap in the sunbeam and loves neighborhood walks. But she’s still full of puppy energy and will make you laugh if you give her a fenced yard or tether so she can zoom and jump. She knows basic commands, is quickly learning leash skills, and sleeps in her crate at night. She does need some training, because because she gets riled up around excitable dogs, but she really just wants to play. She could be happy living with a dog that’s calmer/older (or a dog-compatible cat). Apply to learn more—you won’t regret it, because this dog is made of love and fun!

Interested in meeting Mira? 

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

Our process is as follows:
1.  Review our policies and adoption radius  on our website: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/
2.  Submit an application for review and approval;
3.  MPM Rescue reviews application and checks vet records and references;
4.  MPM foster contacts approved applicant(s) to arrange a home check and meeting with available dog(s);
5.   If there is a good fit, adoption is completed with a contract and fees (payable via check or cash).

The adoption fee is listed here: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/

Dogs from Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
- Spay/Neuter surgery
- Age appropriate vaccinations
- Heartworm test (for dogs over 6mo) and treatment if positive
- Microchip
- Deworming
- Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
- Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

*Please note that the identified breed(s) are best guesses. We very rarely have information on our dogs' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays.*

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Marvin is a character- he's a sturdy little old Dachshund who is strong-willed, loves to cuddle on his terms and will follow you all over, and likes to bark when he wants attention. animal.description:
Outdoor enthusiasts, meet Edith the adventure pup! Edie, as she’s affectionately called by her foster family, is a 33-lb Border Collie/Lab/Terrier mix born in February 2020. This little smarty loves taking her people on hikes and learning new tricks.

Found on the side of the road with a leg injury as a puppy, Edie came to us needing medical help. She also needed to know love and safety, and she got that in spades in her foster home. She’s a happy girl that will make her new family smile every day.

Edie wants a family that loves exploring the world: hiking at state parks and forests, camping, traveling and generally spending lots of time outside. A lover of new places and new things, Edie needs to keep her mind and body active through regular exercise and mental engagement, including puzzle toys and slow feeders, as examples.

Very people oriented, Edie wants to know what’s going on in her home and will follow her family from room to room. She can entertain herself while you work, playing with toys and napping on her bed. Edie can live with older kids, but she might accidentally scratch or knock over littles. Edie can be an only dog or have a canine sibling - as long as her people are around and engaged with her, she’s happy. Kitties are a little too tempting, so only cat-free homes will be considered.

Silly, sweet and just the right amount of sassy, this girl loves to learn! Edie has mastered many basic behaviors, tricks and walks well on a leash. She wants a patient family to help her through a dislike of having her nails done without manhandling; she needs a kind and positive environment in which to thrive.

As wonderful as she is, Edie is not a first-timer’s dog. While out and about, if she’s surprised by something, she reacts by barking and raising her hackles. She can also be slightly selfish with resources, whether toys, food or people. A family with herding breed experience and a background of helping dogs gain confidence and turn to their owners for guidance would be an excellent fit.

Edith is located in Minneapolis/St. Paul. If you think you're a good fit for Edith, please fill out an application at hoabcr.org/how-to-adopt  

As a foster-based rescue, we do not have a central facility to visit. Meet and greets with specific dogs are arranged once your adoption application (not an inquiry email through Petfinder) has been received, processed, and approved. We are located in Minnesota and adopt to an area 400 miles from Minneapolis/St. Paul.

Edith's adoption fee is $350 + MN sales tax. She is spayed, microchipped and up to date on vaccinations.

animal.description:
Apricot or Peaches as her foster mom calls her is a small Chow Chow 3-4 years old. She is a very light shaded red color. At the time of her rescue she had patches of missing hair but did not get diagnosed as having demodex mange until several months into foster care. Her hair has grown back in now and she looks great. Apricot is spayed, microchipped, has all vaccinations, is heartworm negative and weighs 38 pounds. We call her a 'pocket Chow.'
Apricot/Peaches is a fun loving, playful spirit enjoying giving doggie kisses and going on walks. She enjoys sunning outside and chasing squirrels. She sleeps any where but typically is near the bed on a rug. She is a perfect house mate and will make an excellent companion. Traveling she takes in stride and car rides are the best! Children are fine and cats in the house are fine but outside cats would be chased. She does great with smaller dogs and male dogs, we are not sure about other female dogs. Bathing and grooming is ok with her also. Vet visits are OK too.
An approved application is required for adoption. Her adoption donation is 300.00.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Bo. I am a 5 year old male pointer/pit mix that weighs about 60 lbs. I am neutered, microchipped, up to date on vaccinations, and heartworm negative. I have been in this rescue a long time but have only now gained enough confidence to be adopted. You see, I am a very timid guy thanks to an unfortunate past. But since coming into the rescue, I have been with wonderful fosters that showed me love and understanding. I have been trained by Serenity K9 whose awesome trainers totally boosted my confidence. I walk very well on a leash, I know ""place"" and ""sit"", and I am learning other tricks too. My adopter will also receive lifetime support on my training through Serenity K9! Overall, I'm very well behaved, although I am still learning what is and isn't appropriate to chew now that I'm getting to know what being an ""inside"" dog is all about (I am getting a LOT better about this though!). I am house trained and crate trained. I am extremely sweet and do well with all dogs, although I haven't been cat tested (just ask and the rescue will test me!). I would probably do well around children who are polite and sweet with me, but I have not been tested around children. Even though I have gained lots of confidence since coming into the rescue, I am still relatively unsure and insecure, especially with new people and new situations. I will need an owner that can understand my insecurities and show me that this world is a nice and safe one. My adoptive home will need to have at least one female in the household, and men in the family will need to be patient with me as I tend to be less trusting of males. I would probably also do best in a home with at least one other confident dog to be a good role model and friend/playmate for me. My fur is also really soft so you will love petting me, and I love being pet too once I trust you. I'm looking for my furever family...maybe that will be you?

If you are interested in giving Bo a forever home, please visit the link below to fill out an application! http://fureverafterrescue.org/adoption-application.html It is best to submit an application through a computer. We have experienced some problems when applications have been submitted using a mobile device. *When you submit the application, you are not obligated to adopt however it does reserve for you the opportunity to adopt that particular animal. We review them on a first come first served basis. If your application is approved, we will contact you and allow you the opportunity to adopt. If you choose not to adopt, we will contact the next approved applicant. If you have any questions or difficulties, please contact us and we will be glad to help!

Scottie is a sweet guy. He came to us with a bad skin condition and is now healing well. He is still growing his coat back in. He is a great medium sized dog. If he could be for you, please fill out an application today.

The Animal Rescue Project (www.animalrescueproject.org) is committed to the best possible veterinary care for the pets it rescues and it is looking for adopters who will be similarly committed.

All dogs and puppies are given a general check-up when they enter our program. They receive medication to remove any intestinal parasites (worms), fleas, and ticks they may have. Dogs greater than six months of age are checked for heartworm. If heartworm positive, the Animal Rescue Project treats the disease. Dogs and pups receive all age-appropriate vaccinations for distemper, and dogs greater than four months of age are also vaccinated for rabies, in compliance with State of Michigan laws. All dogs will be microchips as well. 

Most dogs and older puppies are spayed or neutered before adoption. In the case of puppies not old enough to be safely sterilized, a $50 deposit is required at the time of adoption and is refunded to the adopter with proof of sterilization.

The Animal Rescue Project requires every adopter to establish an active relationship with a veterinarian no later than 10 days after adoption. Adopters will receive a plan for routine veterinary care at the time of adoption and are expected to work with their vet to complete the plan.

animal.description:
Big Ears, Can’t hear!!!
 She is a spunky girl, full of puppy energy, bouncy and wanting to play. She will cuddle up to you once she gets comfortable. She also loves to follow you around from room to room.

Pretty Miss Ivory is DEAF and has a few other congenital issues that the adopter needs to know and consider when thinking about adding her to their family. 

Ivory is 5 month old, 25# (1/26) looking for a special home willing to teach her all the things dogs should know- and in her case, with Sign Language. Her foster home is working on the basics- sit, down, go outside, yes, come. She is treat motivated- making training a lot more fun. It is good to have done your research on Deaf Dogs before considering adoption of one as there are a lot of good basics to know going into it. 
 Her foster home thinks that she would do best in a home where she would have another friendly/playful dog who could help teach her the ways. She loves her doggie siblings in foster care. 
 They also think she would be better in a house not apartment and a home without young kids. She startles easily from her sleep/being snuck up on (normal for deaf dogs) and for this reason young, playful, unknowing kids might not be great for her. 
 She is working on crate training at night and when her fosters are away at work. She does make a lot of noise to start- but does settle down after time. Her fosters recommend continuing crate training in her future as she loves to drag shoes and clothes all over the house. 

Ivory has early kidney failure based on blood tests. When she arrived at Underdog it was found that she had ectopic ureter (malformation of kidney and a ureter that didn’t connect to bladder correctly). With this, Ivory had the one bad kidney removed. Most dogs do fine with one kidney. However Ivory’s one kidney isn’t fully functioning. She will almost certainly not have a long life (unknown months or years). She will need a special food for her kidney and frequent kidney lab values drawn. This is something an adopter needs to consider. It may also mean added medications and fluid therapy in her future. 

Being both deaf and having kidney issues at birth, it is likely there could be other congenital issues/abnormalities that haven’t surfaced yet. 
 With her light pink skin- it is also good to keep in mind she may have higher risk for certain allergies and skin issues. 
Prior to adoption we encourage reaching out to your personal vet or Underdogs Vet Service to discuss any concerns and to keep in mind the financial responsibility that will come with extra vetting. 

Interested in this sweet dog? Apply today at http://www.underdogpetrescue.org/dog-application

**Please note: Our animals live in foster homes throughout the Madison area. We do not have a shelter where animals are available for daily viewing. Applying is the first step in our process.**

Dogs from Underdog Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
Spay/Neuter
Rabies, Distemper, and Bordetella Vaccinations (as age appropriate-puppy adopters may need to cover some vaccine boosters)
Heartworm Test (for dogs over 6mo)
Microchip
Deworming
Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

Our adult dog adoption fee is $300. Our puppy (under 5 mo) is $375. Our senior dog (over 8 yrs) is $250.

*Please note that all breeds noted are estimates or best guesses. We very rarely have information on our animals' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays*

animal.description:
***All animals listed on our website are in private foster homes. To arrange a meet and greet with a dog, you MUST fill out the adoption application so that it can be sent to the foster parent for review to determine if your home is a match for the dog. If a dog receives multiple applications, we operate on a best-fit basis, not first come first served.***

Hi, my name is Callen! I am a 4-6 year old hound mix with such a big heart. I love attention and give affection as freely as it will be accepted. A couple of months ago I found myself in a county shelter. My sweet personality and unique ear patterns caught my foster's mom eye, and when I was at risk of being euthanized due to a foot injury, she took me home! 

I am crate trained, though I will bark when crated, mostly house trained (I have only had a few accidents when anxious), and harness trained. I currently have four-legged foster siblings and foster mom thinks that I would do best in a forever home with a four-legged companion because I love to play! I also don't love to be alone, so having a fur-friend to keep me company helps when the humans leave. I am currently on an anti-anxiety medication (fluoxetine aka Prozac) to help stop the barking when I am crated and to help me feel more comfortable when I am alone. Luckily it is a cheap medication. It isn't clear whether I will need it long-term, or if I'll be able to be weaned off of it if I no longer have to be crated in my forever home! 

There is a doggy door in my foster home and me and one of my foster siblings are left loose to go in and out as we please. I am not destructive when I am left loose which foster mom really appreciates! She says I am such a good boy, she just wishes I wouldn't bark so much in the crate. I have loved every person I've met. Like I said before, I am super affectionate and I have the most soulful eyes! 

I am very excited to find my perfect forever home! Just to give a quick recap, my perfect forever home would include the following:

1. Another playful doggy
2. A fenced in backyard
3. A family that is around a lot 
4. Affectionate humans
5. A free-standing home so if I am crated my barking won't disturb the neighbors
6. Lots and lots of ear and belly scratchies! 

I am neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations, microchipped, have been dewormed, and am current on my monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives. My adoption fee is $300. If you think I could be the one, please fill out an adoption application on our website: www.secondchancenc.org. Thank you!

animal.description:
UPDATED INFORMATION: EMBER IS NOW IN A FOSTER HOME AND SHE IS DOING GRRRRREAT!  PLEASE READ THIS UPDATED INFORMATION FROM HER CURRENT FOSTER MOM:
Ember is a super sweet, Lab mix (probably mixed with some sort of Bully Breed) who was recently rescued from a high kill shelter after being abandoned in someone's yard and brought into the shelter by animal control. She is a beautiful girl and is estimated to be around three years of age and weighs 57 lbs. She shared her last home with a small dog with no issues and is currently in a foster home with a male dog who is her size and they get along fine. She also got along very well with other dogs at the sending shelter and we have videos to prove it. You can tell by watching her video that she feels kind of lost and really can use some love. We are sure that she will give it back tenfold. She is great with people and thrives on attention. Ember loves to be with her people and will follow them wherever they go.  She sits on command and will sit for her food. She is house trained.  She is crate trained and sleeps in her crate but would love to share a bed with her new family. Ember enjoys playing with toys and running around the yard. She enjoys being outside despite the cold temperatures here in PA and would love having a fenced-in yard to play in. Ember was cat tested at the sending shelter and did an okay job at meeting the kitties. Ember is spayed, micro-chipped and is current with her vaccinations. She has also recently been treated for heart-worm disease and is past her "restricted activity" phase of her recovery. If you would like adopt this beautiful dog, please submit the adoption application through our website OneLifeToLiveRescue.com today! A rescue volunteer will then be in touch with you to answer any questions that you might have and to discuss our ever popular "Foster-to-Adopt" program with you. The recommended adoption donation for Ember is $325 to help with the cost of vet bills. Thank you for your consideration of giving a wonderful home to a beautiful, rescued Lab Mix. We are trying to strictly follow all suggested safety precautions during the COVID-19 pandemic. All recommendations will be respected with as limited person-to-person contact as allowed. Masks are required at this time during any and all interaction with others.. We promise to do our best to keep everyone safe while helping our dogs find loving homes during these trying times.

{s3829code380/}
If you would like to provide this dog a loving home, please fill out a pre-adoption application.

Have a question? Please read our Frequently Asked Questions and Adoption Processed Explained documentation.
_________ B I O ______________

Name:Aleks
Size: ~Large range: 61-100 lbs
Adoption Donation:$250 (applicable sales tax included).Adoption fees may be paid by cash or check.
Other:Neutered Male, Vaccinations current, Microchip, No Cats, Older considerate children only, Not apartment-friendly, Fence Required

*
Aleks needs to go to a home with another dog - he needs a dog buddy to help him feel comfortable and confident!

Alekswould love to be your boy!

Foster Home Feedback

*
No Cats, older considerate children, Not apartment-friendly, Needs a dog buddy and fenced-in yard

12/11/2020: Aleks is sensitive to stress and will need time to decompress in his new home. His favorite place to relax and relieve some stress and anxiety is outside, so a fenced-in yard is a must for him. He is also on medication to help with his anxiety and he does well with taking his pills.

Aleks will do best with a home that has someone who can dedicate time to help him adjust easier and work on any behaviors that may arise. We think a dog buddy would be best for Aleks so he has someone to take cues from. We think this will help make his transition a little easier as well. Aleks loves attention and wants to have it often. He enjoys laying on laps and getting as close as he can. He prefers to have bones to chew on and toys to play with available at all times

Aleks has not been in his kennel for the last couple of weeks and he has done great! He sleeps on a dog bed on the floor of our bedroom and doesn't make a peep all night. Aleks is free to roam the house while we are gone and we have not had any problems.

10/22/2020: Aleks' toe has finally healed and he is ready to go to his furever home! Aleks is such a happy guy and has lots of energy. He loves playing with our dogs, spending time outside, and playing with his tennis ball.

He has done really well with 2 puppies we fostered and is getting along even better with our own dogs. Aleks continues to improve on entertaining himself when we are busy and the other dogs don't want to play. He loves to have plenty of toys and bones to chew on and he also enjoys playing fetch in the house with his tennis balls.

Aleks loves to get lots of attention. He prefers to lay on top of his people and get up close and personal while he gets his pets. Aleks has a tendency to use his paws a lot when he wants attention and it is something we are working on with him

8/19/2020: Aleks still loves to spend time outside. His favorite things to do are sit and watch the birds and squirrels, chase bugs while they fly around, wrestle and play chase with our other dogs, and lay around. He does not like the lawnmower and prefers to be inside while that is going. Aleks was pretty excited to go on walks again after a week-long break due to his surgery. The poor guy broke one of his toes, so he is restricted to his kennel for the time being, but we are going to use this time to get lots of cuddles and pets in.

Along with physical exercise, he also enjoys mental exercise. He's found a love for any toy where he has to figure out how to get treats out. Aleks loves to bat around any ball that he can find. When he's inside and not playing, Aleks enjoys cuddling on the couch and giving his people kisses. He's currently working on sitting before he goes outside, before his leash is put on, and before he gets to go out the gate to begin his walk. Alex loves to be brushed, especially on his head and behind his ears, although he may try to walk away after a while.

At night, Aleks goes into his kennel after being told to "get in your kennel". Sometimes, Aleks will go lay in his kennel before you say anything if he is tired. On the way to the kennel, he occasionally likes to stop and pick up his favorite toy and bring it in his kennel to sleep with him. Aleks sleeps in his kennel and does not make a peep all night, but, I think he would love to sleep on the bed with his people if he could.

8/11/2020: Aleks continues to improve while he's staying with us! He recently found out it's okay to play with toys. When he's in the mood to play, he enjoys throwing his favorite toy in the air and going to get it. Aleks likes to cuddle and be pressed up against his people, which is made a little difficult because of his cone, but we make due. He loves to be scratched on his head! Aleks is also learning to sit, lay down, and shake. I think his favorite part about the training is the hot dogs. Aleks has not chewed on anything he shouldn't or had any accidents. Aleks is also learning to relax inside of the house. He will lay down and also sleep even when he's not in his kennel.

8/7/2020: Aleks is a very energetic boy. He will gladly go on a walk anytime he can. He is a young dog that unfortunately hasn't had a lot of experience or training on the correct ways to meet and interact with new dogs and people. Aleks jumps and barks when meeting new people which can be intimidating due to his size. He also will mouth people when he gets over-excited. We are working on these manors with him and his adopter would need to be willing to continue to work with him. He has already improved a lot in the few days with us. Aleks is very friendly with both but gets excited and is unintentionally rude. He would probably benefit from being with a dog that has experience dealing with younger dogs that don't have perfect etiquette to help him learn how to best interact with new dogs. He does not get along very well with our cat. He barks and whines whenever he sees her. Aleks would probably do best in a cat-free home.

Aleks loves his time outside and would love a family that likes to chill in the backyard as much as he does. We have a fenced-in yard and he seems to relax and calm down when outside. Aleks is a little unsure of the indoors at this point and spends a lot of time pacing and checking closets and corners. He is beginning to get more comfortable.To view additional dogs available for adoption, please see our website: www.4luvofdog.org

animal.description:
HEADS UP: Due to the large number of covid 19 cases in the community, the high hospitalization rates etc, the DFW Dachshund Rescue program will be closed to new adoptions (those that weren't already agreed to before January 1rst) until March 1rst. Most of our volunteers are over 50, and we are using caution until things improve. If you are interested in adopting, contact us after March 1rst.

HIS STORY: Carisi, R.G. (he goes by "R.G.") is a red smooth male dachshund/chihuahua mix who is the size of a small standard dachshund. He is a very intelligent, affectionate but extremely energetic dog. He learns quickly, but needs a home that is very active and has another small to medium sized dog for him to play with. An individual or family considering this dog needs to have the commitment and time to take him regularly to dog sport type classes such as agility or obedience. He is not a dog for an inexperienced owner nor for someone whose own level of physical activity is limited. R.G. will make an active individual or family a delightful and fun companion. d.

Can you give Carisi, R.G. a loving, permanent  home with lots of attention? If so, read the rest of the information below and then contact us for an adoption application. Please be aware that our adoption applications are sent out by postal mail only, and are not sent by e-mail nor are they available on-line.  
 
Before you contact us for an application, please be sure you take some time to read and learn about this breed. Dachshunds are personable and intelligent; however  they  take extra time and patience to housetrain and it is important to know this before you apply to adopt. There are many good books about Dachshunds currently available. Time spent reading one or two of them is well worth it. 
 
ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS: In order to be considered for adoption through DFW Dachshund Rescue Foundation, you must: Be over 21 years of age and have verifiable identification to that effect. Be able to verify that you may have a pet where you live. Live within the immediate Dallas/Fort Worth area. We appreciate your understanding and hope that, if you live outside this area, you will consider adopting a pet from a rescue group that services your particular geographic area. Be prepared to make a donation to our rescue efforts of $250. Be willing to fill out an adoption application, the entire contents of which will be verified upon receipt. Be aware that vet references will be verified to confirm current pets are altered, up to date on vaccinations as well as being annually tested for heartworms and regularly taking heartworm preventative. Have a complete, secure, and safely fenced yard. Be prepared to have a home visit from one of the rescue foundation members as part of the screening process to adopt this dog. During the home visit, our representative will do a brief temperament evaluation of all current dogs in the household. We are unable to adopt to homes where any current dogs exhibit people-aggressive or dog-aggressive behaviors during the home visit. In addition, while we do not preclude adopters who currently own large breed dogs, due to size differential and a dachshund's predisposition to spinal injuries, we are also not able to adopt to homes when the board determines there may be potential for injury to the dachshund. This is to ensure a safe match for our rescued dachshunds. Understand that DFW Dachshund Rescue Foundation has the right to deny any application. 

PHOTOGRAPHY COPYRIGHT: We are fortunate to have Teresa Berg, professional photographer, work with our foundation in regard to photographing rescue dogs in the program. Please note that the Federal Copyright Act protects photographers by giving the author of the photograph the exclusive right to reproduce them. This includes the right to control the making of copies. It is illegal to copy, reproduce or display these photographs elsewhere without the photographer's permission, and violaters of this Federal Law will be subject to its civil and criminal penalties.

LOCATION OF DOGS: Be aware that we do not have a public kennel facility for our dogs; our rescue dogs are fostered with individual families throughout the DFW Metroplex area. 

VET CARE FOR RESCUE DOGS: All rescue dogs are spayed/neutered, fully immunized, tested for parasites (and treated if needed) and tested for heartworms (and treated if needed). In addition, each dog receives a basic blood profile, has a dental cleaning (very young dogs may not need this) and is microchipped. Any infections or other health related issues identified by our veterinary clinic will also be treated. It is our goal to have the dog in excellent health by the time he or she goes to an adoptive home. 

MEETING DOGS: We do not permit visits to any of the rescue dogs until an interested household has filled out an application, and had a reference, vet and home check. Only screened and approved applicants may visit dogs available for adoption through our program. We will not hold dogs for homes that have not yet been approved by our rescue committee. If there is a dog you are interested in applying for, do indicate that in your application, but realize other applicants may be considering that particular dog as well. This is especially true in the case of female dachshunds and puppies. Unlike city animal shelters, we do not use a first come, first served philosophy when it comes to placing dogs from our program. Our goal is to thoughtfully and carefully select the correct home for the dog, and the correct dog for a particular home. The rescue foundation board has final approval on any adoptions for dogs from this program. After the home visit has been completed, the board will consult with the foster parent and/or home visit coordinator and make a determination on the proposed adoption. Decisions by the rescue board are final. 

APARTMENTS/TOWNHOUSES: While we do not preclude adopters who live in apartments or townhouses, be aware that most dachshunds bark a lot and often do not make good apartment/townhouse dogs. We rarely have apartment/townhouse suitable dachshunds available for adoption. If you live in an apartment or townhouse and wish to apply, be aware that you may wait a year or more for a suitable dachshund from our program. In addition, for safety reasons, your apartment/townhouse must have ground floor access. 

CHILDREN: While we do not preclude families with children as potential adopters, it is important to be aware that dachshunds and other small and toy breeds, as a rule, do not respond well to the sudden moves, higher activity level and more impulsive behaviors typically shown by children under 10 years of age. Please be aware that we do not often get dachshunds that are a good match for homes with young children; so anyone applying may experience a longer wait. Instead, you may want to expand your search to breeds that are known to be better with children; such as Labradors, golden retrievers and boxers. Larger dogs may be better able to tolerate the activity, noise and rough play that occur in a home with children. Another choice is to postpone the adoption of a dog until your children are older and more mature and better suited to living with a small dog. 

PUPPIES: We rarely, if ever, have puppies available in our rescue program. If you are interested in a puppy, please contact us for the puppy referral packet to reputable breeders in our area. Please be aware that when we do have puppies or dogs under 1 year of age, they will not be placed in homes where they will be the only dog. 

CAT OWNERS: If you are planning to apply to adopt a dachshund, and own a cat(s), please take into consideration the fact that dachshunds are a hound breed. They tend to view a cat as prey and in many cases, a cat may not be safe living in a home with a dachshund. Occasionally, we have a dachshund who has previously lived successfully with a cat and a dog like this can be adopted to a home with a cat. However, please understand that if we tell you a dachshund(s) will not be good with a cat, we know this to be true, and we will not bring a dog like this for a trial visit with you, for the safety and well-being of your cat. 

Our adoption application has been designed to evaluate potential adopters to ensure that each person who adopts a dachshund is not only aware of the responsibility that comes with adopting a dog, but also to address the suitability and permanence of each dachshund placed in a new home. When considering a new home, our goal is to make the best possible match for each of our rescued Dachshunds. These special dogs deserve the stability of a permanent home where they will be loved, secure and safe for their rest of their lives.

animal.description:
Peanut Berry is a sweet senior chihuahua who still has some pep in her step!
Ever heard of a Velcro dog? That’s her, always wants to be by your side or on your lap. 
She’s no grumpy gal - she gets along with other dogs and with cats!
She is puppy pad trained, so no worries there.
Teeth? Who needs them? Peanut Berry says she only needs one. She has a great appetite and has mastered the puppy dog eyes. It’s hard to resister her looking up at you while you eat dinner. She’s just hoping for a dropped morsel or two. 
Peanut Berry was rescued from a high kill shelter and is now residing in a foster home with a pack of chihuahuas.
She is a gentle and quiet soul who just wants someone to love her in her golden years. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

iHop is also deaf, but he is an intelligent boy and has learned hand signals for come, sit and down. iHop has faced and overcome his challenges in true pit bull fashion. iHop is a very sweet dog who loves life. He would do much better in a rural setting; urban environments give him too much stimuli to react off of. This rural farm boy loves riding on ATVs, tractors and riding mowers. He does not hear vocal warning signs from other dogs and his style of play is not always well received. We suspect iHop suffers from some sort of PTSD. We feel he would make a wonderful companion to someone who has also suffered traumatic experiences. He loves to be around people and is a very good companion. iHop requires daily medication to control seizures.

Bradley needs a home with no small children (under 10 due to energy/playfulness) and without cats. Bradley has done well with other dogs his size. If you would like to make Bradley a part of your family, please fill out an adoption application at www.barktownrescue.org
Adoption Fee: $170

*Due to Covid 19 restrictions some of our new intakes vet scheduling has been delayed. We will still go ahead and schedule your meet and greet even if all the vetting needed has not been completed. Once vetting is complete the approved adopter will be able to take their dog/cat home to their forever home.The shelter software system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only guessing at the dog's predominant breed or breed mix. We strongly encourage you to select your new pet by looking at each dog's individual personality and pet qualities rather than relying on a breed label that is only our best guess.

Our adoption fees vary from $150 and up. All of our dogs are up to date on vaccines, heart worm preventives, and flea/tick medication, and will be spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Portions of your adoption fee also help care for the sick and injured animals that we take in. Thank you for supporting us and considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Lulu is the perfect combination of silly and sweet. She is eager to please, loves her human and dog companions, and believes she's a professional MMA wrestler in her spare time. 

Lulu came to us from a rural shelter in South Carolina with her ten puppies. When they arrived, Lulu had no hair due to severe flea infestation combined with mange, she was extremely underweight, and she had BB pellets embedded in several places under her skin. It took weeks for shelter workers to earn her trust, and as soon as they did, Lulu and her puppies tested positive for parvo despite strict quarantine procedures at the shelter. Luckily, Lulu and her puppies received early treatment and they all survived! Lulu's ten puppies were quickly adopted, but Lulu had a much harder time with trusting both new humans and new environments. 

Lulu's foster mom worked hard for months to build up her confidence, get her used to leash-walking, and to teach her what toys are! Now Lulu absolutely loves to play, especially with other dogs of all sizes. Lulu derives confidence from having another dog and can only go to a home with at least one other medium-high energy pup. She is extremely silly and her zoomies are incredibly fun to watch! 

Lulu is wonderful with women and kids 10+ and does warm up to men given time and treats. She is a pup who loves to use her paws to ""boop"" both human and dog family members, so families should be able and willing to use appropriate positive redirection. 

Lulu is wonderful in the car, walks well on a leash, and is learning that outings and adventures are fun opportunities rather than scary experiences. 

Lulu is crate trained and house trained, as well as medically cleared to go home! She takes prozac once a day to help her with her fears -- she loves to scarf up her meds with peanut butter.

Hi and thank you for your interest in adopting from The Foster Farm!

COVID-19 UPDATE: Due to the overwhelming amount of applications, calls, and emails regarding our currently available pets, we cannot respond to everyone at this time. We appreciate your enthusiasm to rescue a new family member, but please be aware that we simply do not have enough pets in foster care to meet demands at this time. 

WE ARE NOT DOING OUT-OF-STATE ADOPTIONS AT THIS TIME.

In order to help us process your application, please include as much detail and information as possible. Our adoption process is not first come first serve - we work extremely hard to meet the needs of every pet individually, and we do not base our matches on appearances (color, coat length, etc.). 

If you're inquiring about our adoption process, please visit thefosterfarm.org/adopt for information, policies, and procedures. 

If you have submitted an application at thefosterfarm.org/adopt and received the confirmation email from Cognito Forms (your receipt will appear as a copy of the application you submitted), we are reviewing your application. If you are approved to adopt, you will receive an email approval within 72 business hours (Monday through Friday only)! Because our organization is run entirely by four volunteers each with full-time jobs, families, personal pets, and foster animals, we are only able to reach out to approved applicants. 

Thank you so much for your patience and understanding as we all navigate these exceptional circumstances together!

Stay healthy and safe!
The Foster Farm Team

Sampson is a special guy with lots of love to give. He needs an experienced owner with no kids, cats or dogs. He'll need you to provide the love, patience, and treats. while he provides the snuggles and lasting memories.

Sampson is also part of our "Forever Foster Program." This means you provide the loving home and care, while the QCAWC provides his training and medical expenses.

Do you think you could be the one to give Sampson a home to live out his golden years? Please call 309-787-6830 ext 10. to speak with an adoption counselor. Can't adopt? Please like and share to help this very deserving pup find his home.

animal.description:
Miles -
Available for Adoption /or Foster
Friends of Stanly County Animals Rescue

My name is Miles, or as my foster parents call me Mr. Miles.  I'm 4.5 yrs old and weigh 85 lbs. I have been with my foster parents for 4 months basically on a trial run towards adoption. Currently, I walk at least 1 to 4 miles almost everyday at a pace of between 17:30 and19 minutes per mile. I am friends with my foster parent's older female dog and their 4 cats. I don't react at all. 

My best fit would be a home where I am the only dog. I really don't care to be around other dogs. I love my foster family so I automatically protect our home. 

People dropping by the house with their dogs isn't ideal. I like some of the neighbor'dogs, but still feel this need to protect my home.

I enjoy long walks and I'm learning not to pull on the leash.

I’m learning to pull less and pay more attention to my foster's  directions. The gentle lead leash seems to work well for me.

I need someone who can continue to teach me. I really enjoy being outside so I can walk, smell, see the scenery. This may sound funny, but I love watching the buzzards fly.  When an emergency vehicle comes by I have a beautiful howl that sounds like the siren.  I do have separation anxiety when my foster parents are out of the room or leave the house. I pant and whine, but eventually I do go back to my spot on the couch or floor.  I try to offer my paw wanting love and affection. I love to play with toys and some minor fetching, but only when I’m on the mood.  I love a lot of affection, love, and treats; except for peanut butter, which surprised my foster mother.  I do love car rides.  My ideal home would be where I am the only dog, and I'm able to go out and walk. My other personality loves being a couch potato.  I do not like dog crates. I'm not sure why..  When my foster parents were trying to crate train me, I got one of my front paw pads stuck in the crate door trying to get it open and eventually broke the latch on the door.  Since then I have been sleeping in my foster parents bedroom on the floor at night. Ideally, I would like a home where I don't have to crated. I can still use some training, especially while out walking or letting someone know it's time for a bathroom break.  Currently, I go out 3-4 times a day.  I will not poop in my own yard, although I will while out walking.  My foster parents have tried to train me to poop in the yard, but I won’t always.  I do know how to sit, come, paw, and up, but I sometimes don’t want to listen.  While walking I know cross means I speed up my walk and cross street.  Turn means turn left.  Right means turn right and stay on right,  I'm still working with this sometimes.  Heal I am still working on.  I am good with kids, but I would not want a child under age 5 as I may jump up on them or they could hurt me and not mean to.

Adoption Application Link:  
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdJcO2I9-K8FMjB9CNflX9xbOpIRjc0gyxzYtdkRn6zPluovw/viewform

Nina is such a calm girl and she loves to snuggle. She is gentle and loving. Nina  likes to play with squeaky toys but doesn’t seem to indulge in rough housing with other dogs. She gets along well with other dogs but has not been tested with cats. Nina would do well with respectful children over the age of 10 years. 

Nina loves to go for a walk on her leash and does well on car rides. Nina would like a home where her people are home most of the time and she would LOVE a home where she could sleep in the big bed and snuggle under the covers. 

Nina does have some separation anxiety and will cry and bark when left in her crate.  Nina is crate and house trained but like all dachshunds she will need to be reminded and encouraged to go outside on a regular schedule. Like  all dogs she will need to be confident in her environment to have good potty habits. All rescue dogs go thru a period of adjustment so understanding and patience is important. 

Nina loves to eat and is not a fussy girl . Nina takes medication daily to aid in seizure prevention. Nina has not had a seizure since coming into rescue and her vet feels as though she may be tapered off of this medication. 

Nina is ready for a forever home.  Are you ready to welcome Nina home? Apply to adopt her today!

animal.description:
This is Lucho, a three-year-old, ten pound deer-head Chihuahua who is very excited to meet his new family!  He loves being with people and is always looking to see what is going on.  He wants to be right in the middle of his foster family's activity and he loves to take long walks or play in the yard no matter the weather.  He also loves playing with his plush toys and likes to carry them out in the yard with him.  Lucho loves affection and pets!

Lucho is a happy go lucky guy who adores his people but he does have some Chihuahua quirks which would make his ideal home a single owner with no other pets.  Lucho does show some resource guarding when he is on the couch or bed and may bite.  For example, if he is cuddling on the couch with his person and someone else comes over to give affection to the person he is sitting with, Lucho may bite them.  His previous owner was a single, older person who did not take him out much or introduce him to many people so he is learning to adjust to different experiences .  Lucho loves everyone he has met since moving in with his foster mom but please take things slowly.

Lucho finds other dogs scary at first but can adjust to being around them if they are easy-going and not confrontational.  He had a foster sister who was a three-pound Chihuahua, and still found her a bit scary but he did like lying next to her on the couch since she seemed to like me.  Right now he is living with two other small male dogs and while he tolerates them he would prefer to have his owner all to himself.  Lucho does have a bit of barrier aggression with the other dogs and becomes very reactive when they go near his crate or if he sees them through the sliding glass door.

We will be prioritizing applications that are a single owner with no other pets but we may consider two people if they have experience dealing with resource guarding.  We would also consider a single person with one dog who would may be a good fit for Lucho.  Please detail your experience with resource guarding on your application.

If you are interested in finding out more about Lucho, please fill out an application on our website by copying and pasting the following link into your browser:

http://bit.ly/2JnZqK5

Lucho is being fostered in Millbury, MA and the adoption fee is $300.

"Like" Broken Tail Rescue on Facebook! https://www.facebook.com/brokentailrescue/

NOTE:  Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

We expect that all adopted dogs will enroll in a formal dog training class with their new owners.  Obedience and training classes are an excellent way to learn more about your newly adopted dog, gain handling and training experience, and improve your relationship with your pet.

animal.description:
Negan is a handsome liver colored German Shepherd estimated around three and a half to four years of age. Negan came to us through a rural Kentucky shelter after being involved in a court case due to neglect. Although Negan has had a rough few years he is ready to put that behind him and find his fur-ever home.

Negan is the sort of boy who doesn't believe anyone should be a stranger for long and that he should always be the life of the party. Negan has a very outgoing personality and is quick to make friends most of the time. Although there are times he can be a bit shy they are definitely few and far in between. Negan is a tripod but that does not slow him down in the slightest and he loves to get out and run and play. He can be very bouncy and jumpy with those he knows but has mostly learned not to jump on new people. Negan loves to go for walks and hikes and exploring creeks when he gets the chance. He also greatly loves to play fetch as well as tug games. Negan does very well in the house and is an overall well-mannered boy. Negan has been around children as young as 2 years of age and done okay.

Negan loves to romp and roughhouse with other dogs. He is quick to make friends and even quicker to push them around. Negan does live with other shepherds and has lived with dogs as small as 15 lb but he can be a bit of a bully in the play yard at times. If he is allowed to get his way he would definitely be a trouble starter. Thankfully the other dogs he is around tolerate him well and just keep playing. They are particularly fond of chase games and Negan is happy to entertain. Negan does come from a background where food and water were scarce so he does have some resource guarding with the other dogs but continues to get better every day. Negan has been around a cat briefly and done okay but we would like another cat test before he could be placed in a home with a cat.

Negan is a playful, adventurous guy who is looking for a home that will give him the patience, exercise, and love he deserves. If you're the home for Negan please email tierhavenrescue@gmail.com for an adoption application or visit Tierhaven.rescuegroups.org for FAQs

animal.description: Sweet Happy needs a permanent foster or loving home for the time she has left. We are unsure of how long that would be but she does have a medical issue. She cannot open her mouth normally and therefore can only eat canned food. We are unsure of what has happened to her to cause this, probably some sort of trauma. She gets an antiobiotic for her mouth monthly to keep down the infection and she has rimadyl and gabapentin daily. All of these meds would be paid for by the rescue for sure in foster and if an adoptive home could be found and cannot afford, the rescue will take care of it. She seems to be pain free when on this combination of meds and loves to play with toys and go for walks. She is also hearing impaired, may hear a little but not much. Probably due to ongoing ear infections left untreated. Because of her hearing impairment we do prefer a fenced in yard but it is not mandatory. She does love to play with her toys in the yard. Happy currently is in a foster home with two other male dogs. One she is totally fine with but wants to be rather bossy with the second one. She does have some food aggression with other dogs only so bowls need to be picked up after eating and she should be kept separate at feeding time. Happy has many needs but is a wonderful, loving girl so deserving of a loving place to call home. Happy is a lab mix and currently weighs about 37 lbs. She could gain another 5. We think she is about 10 years old. She is housetrained and crate trained and does not get into any trouble when left with the run of the house. She has not been around children since we had her but we think older respectful children would be fine. We are also unsure about cats but her temperament is so sweet we don't think they would be a problem. She is fully vetted. Please consider opening up your home to this sweet girl. If interested in Happy, please email hartmanshounds@gmail.com or call Peggy @ 440-452-1619. Her adoption fee would be very minimal to the right home.

animal.description:
Daisy is a senior at 12-years. She is a big girl boxer/mastiff mix. She is the sweetest girl and VERY low energy. Do to her age she does have arthritis and a rare form of diabetes that will require meds for the rest of her life. She is also partially deaf.

Daisy is trained not to get on furniture. She loves walks or a fenced yard. No tie-outs for this girl. She is good with other dogs and cats, but would feed separately, she does guard food.

She loves her crate or any den like space, but once comfortable she does love a dog bed and laying around her humans.

Daisy is not a fan of car rides, or going to the vet . She will not act out at the vet, it is just hard to get her in the door. She is very much a homebody and loves napping. We absolutely adore this girl.

If you would like to meet Daisy 1 fill out an app at www.adoptastray.com
All SAAP animals are vet checked, UTD on vaccines, spayed/neutered, micro chipped, and given flea and heartworm preventative as age appropriate.

http://www.adoptastray.com/adoptable-animals/

Have questions:
Please email us at saap@adoptastray.com for more information about this animal or to answer any questions you may have. You may also contact us at (859)391-1234.

Completing the online application when you find an animal you are interested in speeds up the adoption process. We can hold your application on file for a period of time if you are still looking for that perfect new family member.

http://www.adoptastray.com/dog-adoption-application/

animal.description:
Thank you for choosing rescue.  To begin the process please fill out an application here:  http://goo.gl/forms/XPuk6w9615GXqo0x2

This is my foster dog...if you or anyone you know is interested in adopting this dog please contact: www.DogGoneInn.com

Name: 		Harriet 
Gender: 	Spayed 
Color:		Black Brindle
DOB:		11/18/2019
Breed:		Cane Corso
Weight:	70 lbs
Notes:  I am timid and would do best in a quiet home without children.  I do great with dogs and cats though! My third eyelid protrudes, but it doesn't bother me.  My foster mom says it makes me unique and pretty.  I have been experiencing separation anxiety and will need help to trust that you’re my forever home. 

There is an adoption process along with a donation.

Please bring your dog (if you have one), and a martingale collar with a leash, should we move forward.  We recycle theirs for the next dog :)  I have attached a picture of a martingale collar.  If you cannot find one, we do sell them at the daycare for 10-15.  Purchasing one from us allows us to fit it properly and it helps to benefit the rescue.  We carry leashes too, the collar and leash set are 30.  Adoption donations vary depending on the dog's age and medical expenses.  Typically they start at 650 and go up from there.  We realize this is a larger donation, however we have no state funding like shelters do.  That being said, dogs do come to you fully vetted.  They have been fixed, given distemper, bordetella, rabies, heartworm tested, de-wormed, on prevention for heartworm, fleas, ticks, intestinal parasites and microchipped.  Additionally we have paid for the microchip registration for life. 

*Please note we make every effort to have our dogs altered prior to adoption, if we cannot spay/neuter clauses will be in the contract.

*Please come down to the Dog Gone Inn in Manlius to meet us!

Thank you for choosing rescue! 

Don't forget to like us and follow us on Facebook, we get new animals in regularly.

*Please submit an application here: http://goo.gl/forms/XPuk6w9615GXqo0x2 and come down to the Dog Gone Inn in Manlius to see me or (315) 728-9344 or www.DogGoneInn.com or DogGoneInn@Yahoo.com or www.facebook.com/DogGoneInn

animal.description: This is Bread from our Bread and Butter tandem that we recently rescued together. Both dogs were extremely neglected, matted, and covered in fleas when we found them. The amount of fur we took off of Bread was almost equal to half of his body weight! But all that neglect didn’t prevent Bread from being a very sweet and loving dog. From what we observed at the shelter, he’s friendly with people and indifferent to dogs when outside. He is very dominant when he is being walked and pulls a lot on his leash. He is a bit apprehensive at first with people which is probably due to the severe neglect he was subjected to. He has also previously shown fearful aggression and is for experienced adopters only. Despite all the hardship we know Bread will make an incredible pet companion for whoever ends up being lucky enough to adopt him at https://amaanimalrescue.org/pet/bread/

She is leash reactive to dogs while on walks and will need a home who is committed to engaging her with a trainer to help her in this area. Sheeba’s current foster does not have other animals but she came from a home with other dogs and was reported to be friendly. Sheeba’s favorite activities include some serious squirrel stalking, surveying the back yard, laying in the sun, and checking on her person. She is happy to clean off your kitchen counters if you leave things within easy reach. Sheeba is a sweet dog who loves to be near her humans and will be a wonderful companion for just the right family.

animal.description:
I LOVE TO GIVE KISSES

Lexington LOVES to meet new people. He is very eager to kiss you and become friends. Maybe you will give him one of his favorite marrow bones. This boy likes to follow you around the house, go for a short walk or have a cuddle and kiss on the couch. 

Lexi is a real character. He is goofy, very curious and animated. He adores other dogs and is desperate to get close to them to kiss them and play. Lexi is a 7 year old, 60 pound, red nose Pit Bull. In behavior he is like a puppy, he has little explosions of excitement, likes to put things in his mouth and can be mouthy when he is excited. A home with a single person, couple, or family with older children would be suitable for him. They would need to be tolerant of his sometimes puppy like behavior. 

Lexi is neutered, and house trained. He comes with a collar, leash and 3 free training sessions for you to learn proper handling, leash walking and how to give corrections. Our rescue provides ongoing lifetime support for our adopters and are always available by phone, and in person to help you assimilate your new baby into your home. Let us know if you would like to meet Lexington and get some kisses.
