animal.description:
Please email info@prairiepaws.org to fill out an application and arrange an appointment to meet the pet. Want to get a head start on the application? Here's the link: DOG ADOPTION APPLICATION: https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/PPAS/Dog

Vixen is a magical male heeler mix puppy. His estimated DOB is 09/23/2020. He came to our shelter as an owner surrender and his weight at intake was 12 lbs. He is so ready to venture into puppyhood with you! He is super smart and wants to learn how he can become your favorite family member. Are you ready to adopt? Are you ready for puppyhood? We estimate him to grow up to be a medium-sized bundle of joy. Vixen adoption fee is $225 and includes a medical exam, sterilization, age-appropriate vaccines, dewormer, heartworm test, and microchip

Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. As we get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

All PPAS puppies and dogs are up to date on all of their vaccines (including rabies if age appropriate), and will be micro chipped and registered in the adopter's name at the time of adoption. Adopters get a free consultation at an area vet partner within 14 days of adoption. Any dog that is six months of age or older will be tested for Heartworms and if found negative, will be kept on Heartworm prevention during their shelter stay, after the adoption it is up to the adopter to continue the highly recommended Heartworm preventative treatment. Also all PPAS shelter dogs are treated with a monthly topical flea/tick preventative and we ask that adopters continue that treatment as well. Per state law we sterilize all shelter pets before they begin their new fabulous lives with their new families.  

Our animals change daily, so please check our lists of adoptable dogs and adoptable cats frequently. Once you find an animal you’d like to adopt, the next steps are to complete an application and request a meet and greet with the foster. Make sure to be thorough and help us understand why you’re interested in that particular animal — and why your home is a great fit. Based on your answers we may even have a better fit for you.

Adoption fees:  Adoption fees must be paid in full at the time of adoption – no partial payments are accepted.  All major credit cards are accepted.  Adoption fees vary. 

Taking your animal home:  The State of Kansas requires that all cats and dogs must be sterilized (spayed/neutered) before going to their new homes.  In most cases, animals will have already been sterilized before being placed on the adoption floor and you will be able to take your new companion home with you the day of adoption.  However, if the animal is not yet sterilized, they will need to stay at the shelter and we will schedule the surgery on the next available date (usually within a week).  All cats must go home in a carrier.

If you are interested in this pet, please either email Prairie Paws Animal Shelter at info@prairiepaws.org, for an application or visit our website @ prairiepaws.org for more information.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to lauren.baird.htar@gmail.com

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1.
For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team member will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time.

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE:
http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Elijah was a stray. He just turned up on someone's porch one day in terrible shape, dragging about two feet of chain with him everywhere he went. Who knows how long he had been on his own! His fur was dirty and matted and clumps of hair were missing. 

At first, he growled. He was scared, unsure what to expect from strangers. But as those strangers set about helping him--finally freeing him from the dragging chain, shaving the dirty mats off his body--he began to open up. With just a little kindness, he seemed to become a whole new dog. 

We are still learning so much about Elijah. For instance, we're learning that he loves big fluffy beds and toys. He loves playing tug-of-war and playing with his tennis ball. For all we know, this might be the first time in his life that he has ever enjoyed such simple luxuries. It's hard not to spoil him!

Elijah loves getting head scratches. He follows you around and does great in his crate. He is looking for a home with limited stairs as his back legs do have some lameness. He also has some eyesight/hearing problems but that isn't stopping him. He is very mild mannered and patient. Can you give him a loving home that he deserves?

Adoption Coordinator: Lauren B
Location: Foster Home

The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee INCLUDES spay/neuter and microchip.

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description:
Karma is a big sweetheart! She is very outgoing and friendly. She absolutely loves people and always has a "smile" on her face! 

Karma has been in a foster home and foster mom says:

"She seems to be house trained.  We take her out every two hours or so but she has never had an accident. Twice she has sat in front of the back door to indicate she needs to go out. She never barks or scratches the door. 

She has fallen in love with our neighbor’s dog who is not returning the feeling. We think she would do best in a house with another sweet dog. 

She is learning to walk on a leash. It is a slow walk as she sniffs everything!! 

Our adjectives are well-mannered, wonderful temperament, cuddly and quiet. She is playful on occasion but doesn’t seem to understand fetch with a ball. Haha. She loves the Kong toy we got her, especially with
peanut butter. Overall, just an easy, good-natured dog."

We rescued Karma and her 3 puppies as strays. Her date of birth is 11/5/2017 and she weighs 73lbs.

You can submit an adoption application for this sweet girl at http://www.fayettefcar.com/applicationform, where you can also review FCAR’s adoption requirements.

All FCAR adoptable dogs have been spayed or neutered, are current on all vaccines, on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, microchipped, and come with a 30-day pet health guarantee. The adoption fee is $95 with an approved application. A fenced yard is required for Karma.

animal.description:
Hey everyone, my name is Diamond, a female Pitbull mix weighing 60lbs, at 11 years young. While a little timid at first, I am a sweet loving pup looking for my forever home. I still become increasingly excited when my foster family plays with me. Although slightly older I am still full of life exhibiting my spunky, playful personality while playing with kids, dogs and toys. When not being active I love laying in the sun and being outdoors with others. I am crate and potty trained, but do not do well being restrained. I take pain medication for arthritis and am on a specific diet avoiding grain based foods which cause itchy lumps and bumps. I am an older dog but still love to play like a pup. I am looking for a family to love me unconditionally and accommodate my needs.

If you are interested in Diamond, please complete an adoption application at lastdaydogs.com

animal.description:
Bella and Lucy are best friends that have been together their whole lives.  Now six and half years old, these girls are very sweet family dogs anyone would love to own.  Their elderly owners were unable to continue caring for them and asked us to find them a new home.  Medium in size, Bella is a pretty petite Lab mix and Lucy is a cute chunky Beagle/Cattle Dog mix.  Both listen well and are very well behaved loving pups.  Bella and Lucy are accustomed to being around older children and other dogs.  These ladies prefer a calm quiet household where someone is home most of the day.  Bella and Lucy are easy-going and just want to be your buddies.  They are perfectly content just hanging out around the house and making sure you’re never lonely.  Neither is really into toys, but they do enjoy taking a daily stroll.  They also enjoy occasional trips to the park and ride well in the car.  Because of their prior situation, they may need some additional housetraining.  Both prefer going on grass if kept to a regular schedule.  A fenced in yard is needed to keep them safe when outside.  Bella and Lucy are really quite special and deserve a wonderful home.  Will that be with you?  

To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

animal.description:
Meet Drew! This handsome retriever mix is looking for a home to call his own! Drew has a comical, goofy personality, and is ready to make his new family laugh every day with his goofy antics. Drew is a high energy, fun loving dog who would love a family to take him on daily jogs through the neighborhood, and throw the ball for him in the backyard. He LOVES toys, and will happily entertain himself tossing his toys all throughout the yard. 

His foster reports he is learning to play fetch with his ball, and is getting really good about bringing it back each time you throw it. Drew also enjoys swimming in his foster's pool, and has recently discovered how fun sprinklers can be! Drew loves to chew, and will happily chew on an antler or bone on a comfy bed to pass the time. Drew is a smart kiddo, and is looking for a family who will continue all the good manners he is working so hard to learn. This clever boy already knows how to "sit" and "lay down" when asked! 

Drew has worries about meeting new people, and is looking for a home that will make sure he feels safe and comfortable. He will do best in an adult only home, with a yard, in a quiet neighborhood. Drew does not do well with frequent changes in his environment, and lots of hustle and bustle in the house makes him nervous. 

He is crate trained and house broken, and has already mastered the doggie door in his foster home. He is working on his leash manners, and does best when walked in a no pull harness. He rides well in the car as well, and would be a great errand running companion. If you are looking for an active canine companion, Drew is the one for you - schedule an adoption appointment today! 

To learn more about Drew, watch this video: https://youtu.be/27U_Qzyyp1Y
Watch Drew play with his pal, Colton: https://youtu.be/oEbi-bBJhBM

animal.description:
Raven is always sporting a happy smile for everyone she meets.
Raven is a peppy girl with lots of great energy! If you're looking for a playful pooch, Raven is your girl! So loving and sweet, Raven is always out for a little attention and maybe even a few treats. 1-year-old Raven has captured the hearts of both volunteers and staff, who adore her delightful personality. Eager to please, Raven walks very well on the leash and even sits for a treat. Though she came to us as a stray, Raven is very people-focused and loves to be pet. She even loves jumping up to give you sweet kisses. Raven can't wait to meet you, come pay this angel a visit!



All pets at this shelter are up-to-date on shots and will be altered and micro-chipped upon adoption.  Please visit our shelter to meet the many adorable orphans that are available for adoption.  When inquiring about a specific animal you saw on this website, please include the ID number associated with the animal. We are open 7 days a week from 12pm-4:30pm Monday thru Friday and 12pm-4:30 Saturday & Sunday. For information and/or directions call 732-922-0100 or email TintonFallsahs@ahsppz.org

There is an adoption fee required.  The Society cannot accept personal checks but we do accept Visa, MC, AE, and cash.

                               IMPORTANT
 As part of our adoption process, we must have proof of residency.  Homeowners must show proof of ownership; a valid lease that states "pets ok" is required for renters before an adoption can be approved. If you do not have a lease with your landlord you will need a notarized letter.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ ALL THE INFORMATION IN THE DOG'S PROFILE, AS WELL AS THE INFORMATION ON OUR WEBSITE, www.niagaradogrescue.org , BEFORE EMAILING US WITH QUESTIONS. OUR VOLUNTEERS USE UP VALUABLE TIME ANSWERING QUESTIONS WHERE THE ANSWERS ARE READILY AVAILABLE ON THE WEBSITE. 
SINCE WE ARE ENTIRELY VOLUNTEER RUN AND RECEIVE A HIGH VOLUME OF APPLICATIONS, IT MAY TAKE AT LEAST 2-3 WEEKS BEFORE AN ADOPTION TEAM MEMBER CAN RESPOND TO YOUR APPLICATION. PLEASE BE PATIENT.
WE ARE FOSTER BASED, THEREFORE WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY.  MEET & GREETS FOR DOGS IN CANADA WILL NOT BE ARRANGED UNTIL AN ADOPTION APPLICATION IS APPROVED. THANK YOU!!!

Please visit our website at http://www.niagaradogrescue.org or apply for adoption at http://www.niagaradogrescue.org/adoption/

Name: Carl
Weight: 52lbs
Age: 5 years
Gender: male
Breed: English hound
Color: red/white

Good With Adults: yes
Good With Kids: no, would be best for an adult only home
Good With Other Dogs: yes
Good With Cats: unknown, hasn't been exposed
Crate Trained: yes
Energy Level: high; he would make a great running partner!
Can be handled/touched: yes
Barker: ONLY if left outside
Escape Artist: yes, he can easily climb a fence. He will need to be leashed outside until he is comfortable
Food Aggressive: no, but is highly food motivated and will go after scraps
Walks on Leash: yes

Backstory: My name is Carl and I am a 5 year old gentleman! I was found in Kentucky as a stray, but I really like couches and table scraps, so I may have been in a home at one point before coming to Canada. That being said, I need parents who can teach me boundaries and proper training around couches and people food so I don't thinks it's always mine. It might take me a bit to warm up, but once I feel comfortable, I'm a happy boy. I would do better in an adult only home, because kids can be overwhelming for me. I'm a very loving boy who would do best in an active home (I love to run!) and who can help me get all my energy out. I love my toys and of course curling up on a soft bed. I am a hound who likes to follow his nose, so no little critters please and make sure to keep an eye on me when I'm outside - I can climb! I can't wait to meet you and be part of your family!

animal.description:
Jaypaz is a handsome boy! He came to us as a lost dog and hasn't been claimed. Jaypaz is about 50 lbs, heartworm negative and up to date on shots. We think he's a 'young adult'.

He sits to be leashed, likes to play with toys and will share them with his people. He does jump up and is a bit mouthy, but this is easy to work on with training. 
He is very playful with other dogs, he's played with a male and a female here at the shelter. 

A volunteer who spent time with Jaypaz at the shelter reports: Seems young, VERY playful, a little mouthy but it's easy to redirect his attention with a toy. Enjoys attention and wants to give kisses. 
WATCH JAYPAZ'S VIDEO where he plays with his friend, Patches! 

Adoption fee includes vaccinations, spay/neuter, heartworm test, and microchip.

animal.description:
Age: 1 years.
Weight: 40-45lbs
Good with dogs: Yes
Good with cats: No
Good with kids: Yes - Older teenagers
Energy Level: High

Available for Adoption: Now (Accepting applications Now) - Applications need to be approved before a meet and greet will be set up for any Fetching Hearts Rescue dogs.

Meet Nick! This handsome boy came in as a stray to the shelter.  We were very surprised that nobody came to claim him.  He was found just roaming the streets.  Nick is looking for a family who is dog savvy and will continue his training skills.  As he is still young, he would like to learn how to become a good boy and obey his family.  He would love to have another doggie friend to play with in a fenced yard. He will need dog savvy kids who are older as he can be jumpy when excited.  This boy will be a great with structure, continuous training, and someone very active.  If you want a very active friend, apply for Nick today!!

If interested in Nick, please email to inquire at: SCREENING.FETCHINGHEARTS@GMAIL.COM OR COPY LINK BELOW TO APPLY AND FILL OUT AN APPLICATION: https://www.fetchingheartsrescue.org/adoption-form-online to fill out an application.

Unless otherwise indicated, all dogs adopted through Fetching Hearts have received the following before being available for adoption:

Thorough veterinary examination

All routine annual vaccinations, including Rabies, DHLPP, Bordatella (Kennel Cough), Heartworm Test, Fecal Test, Deworming, Microchip, Flea and Tick Prevention and Heartworm Prevention.

Spay/Neuter
All dogs are quarantined for two weeks outside of the shelter (puppies four weeks) to ensure they don't break with disease.

VETTING NOTE: Fetching Hearts Rescue completely vets our dogs thoroughly to the best of our knowledge based on communication with our Southern Vets. If anything is brought to our attention, we treat the dog. After adopting the dog, you will be responsible for following up with all vetting going forward.

HEARTWORM NOTE: Dogs who were treated for Heartworm can test positive up to 4-6 months after last treatment. All dogs are immediately put on Heartguard/Ivermectin following the treatment to kill the Heartworm larvae. All dogs should be re-tested after 5-6 months from the last Heartworm treatment.

animal.description:
Axel is a 5 year old male Husky mix. A nice person found him as stray and brought him to the shelter. Check out his gorgeous black coat with silver highlights and then glance into his beautiful light blue eyes! This guy is a show stopper. This handsome boy most likely has never been an inside dog as he is scared of being indoors. Because he is still learning to adapt to being indoors, he would do best in a home that has a fenced in backyard for him to run around and explore. He would not do well in an apartment. Axel can be shy of new people at first, but once he warms up to you, he enjoys the attention. He has an independent personality but enjoys being petted and loves going on walks and performs well on a leash. Because he can be shy around new people, he would likely do best in a home with no children. He is friendly with other dogs and a happy natured guy. He is not housebroken at this time. Axel is heartworm positive but don’t worry, the shelter pays for his treatment. He is also up to date on his vaccinations, microchipped and neutered. 

ADOPTION HOURS: 

We are currently adopting out animals by appointment only Tuesday through Sunday 1:00 P.M. through 4:00 P.M. with an approved application. To fill out an application, please go to: https://collierville.com/departments/animal-services/animal-shelter-pet-adoption and email it to: casinfo @colliervilletn.gov
Once your application has been approved, we will call you to set up an appointment.

animal.description:
Meet our lovable Amber!

She is very playful and sweet personality. 

She is a mixed of French Bull dog and a Pit bull terrier. 
The French Bulldog Pitbull mix unites two smart and good natured breeds.

She has short legs and probably won't grow too big - 

She has been around other dogs and kids - Amber will be a great family pet or for a solo very active companion as she still a puppy.

As with all rescued fur kids; they are going to need training, love reinforcement; as you know they all come from a tough beginning on their lives and the art of adopting a rescued creature is to bring them to be the best they can be with love and patience.

Her adoption fee includes being spayed; she has received her 3 core puppy vaccines, dewormed, and a free health check up through a local participating vet clinic.

Ready to give her a forever home? Please follow the instructions and start with completing an application at the following link: http://aaofus.org/adoption-application.html

We are scheduling meet & greet adoption appointments and keeping a distance protocol. No appointments will be made unless we have received an application; therefore, we can match you with the best fit for you. Appointments are scheduled late afternoons.

Please text at 619-576-0747 or email veronica.aaofusa@gmail.com or visit our website at www.aaofus.org and complete our application at the following link:
http://aaofus.org/adoption-application.html

Due to high volume of calls; NO PHONE calls are accepted at this time - therefore, please text us or email us.

LIVE!! LOVE!!! RESCUE!! ADOPT A HOMELESS PET AND SAVE A LIFE!!!

Follow us on Instagram @aaofus

animal.description:
Lizzy came to us in April. She was missing hair over her entire body. After months and months of cultures, skin scrapes, testing, etc... we FINALLY got her skin issue under control and her fur has grown back beautifully! 
*She is still currently on medications/sees a dermatologist for this issue and will need to remain on medications until possibly January or further. 
**Rockstar Rescue will continue to pay for and monitor her progress with these medications even after adoption.
***Lizzy is currently NOT spayed, due to her ongoing skin issue, but once an adoption is confirmed she will be scheduled for surgery at Rockstar's expense immediately.

Lizzy IS ACTIVE! She needs activities. Hiking, running, etc... She requires a yard and MUST have a red ball at all times, LOL!
She was previously adopted to a family with a 3yr old and did magnificent! (She was returned due to her skin issue before we had it fully under control)

Lizzy is NOT for a first-time dog/pet owner. She needs an experienced handler/leader and lots of patience, understanding and love. She can be non-engaging at times when her focus is her ball. She can be a handful when she sees other dogs on walks, but quickly redirects and walks great!

We'd love for you to meet our girl but first tell us a bit about your living circumstances; house/apt, children/others in the home, work schedule, experience, etc...

Thanks

animal.description:
MEET POLLOCK!!

Pollock can be pretty shy at first, but will warm up and be a very playful dog. He loves his toys and loves to play tug. He has a lot of energy during play time and is very calm when playtime is over. Pollock does very well when being walked on a leash, but will get excited and pull when he see's the ducks at the park (speaking from personal experience). He does very well sleeping in his kennel at night and has learned to use the doggy door to come in and out. Pollock also did very well with the other dog in the Foster house and they even get walked together at very close range. In a recent meet and greet, Pollock did not take well to a potential adopters dog. He became nervous on the drive to the meet and greet and that could have had something to do with it, but because of this, The foster believes that Pollock may not like car rides just yet and may be dog selective

Pollock needs an adopter who understands fearful dogs and can work with him. He needs to learn how to trust people and find out there is someone out there that will show him the love and patience he needs.

If you are interested in Pollack, please visit our website www.underdogaz.com for our application.

animal.description:
My name is Hobbes.  I came to MAS back in 2015.  My D.O.B. is 4//13/14.  I was still a youngster.  I was super hyper and quite the handful for being a short little guy.  I was adopted out a couple times, and came back within a week or so.  I tend to get super excited in certain situations, and my new owners just could not handle the energy.  I really need a patient home that can give me time to get used to my new environment, and take things slow with me.  I am a cuddler, and I love to walk, but need to be in more of a rural setting where I don't respond to all the noise of a busy bustling area.  I really could be your best friend.  I would need a home without kids and cats. They both make me nervous. 

Meet-Your-Match Canine-ality color is: Orange Busy Bee!!
For safety's sake, we are looking for homes with physical fenced in areas.

animal.description: Wrangler is here to lasso your heart! He is about 1 to 2 years old but sometimes acts like an 8 week old puppy! We think he is a Lab and Pointer mix. Wrangler has a lot of energy and is looking for a very active family that can wear this boy out mentally and physically every day. Due to his size and puppy-like energy, he isn't the best match for apartment living and would do better in a home with a yard for him to gallop around in. He is also still figuring out manners and what not to put in his mouth - everything is a chew toy to this goofy guy! Once he masters his leash skills, he'd be an excellent running buddy and he's up for whatever high flying adventure you throw at him. He loves snuggles and giving kisses when he's not playing. He gets along well with the dog he is fostered with, although he does like being top dog, and so far seems to be leaving the cat alone in his foster home. The only time this happy boy's tail stops wagging is when he's sleeping. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Wrangler, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Zoey!
My two favorite things are sleeping in bed with my foster mom and running around! And maybe chew toys and treats-but almost every dog loves those, so they don't really count, right? My foster mom says I need a yard for exercise and an active person. I am excellent on the leash, and have only ever pulled at all when we saw a cat. I don't like cats by the way... I am working on learning commands, and sometimes don't listen when I know my foster mom doesn't have treats. I get along well with other dogs we meet, but probably won't be the greatest pet for a young child due to my energy. I love Kongs, Buffalo horns and other indestructible toys. I still loves to chew and eat things like all young dogs do.. I am house trained and crate trained, but I don't like being in the crate when when my foster mom is home. I am very affectionate and love everyone, sometimes too much according to my foster mom! I am about 45 lbs, still need to gain. I am very strong and muscular , sometimes get excited, and don't realize how big I am! But I am still a cuddle bug and would love to sit in my person's lap if I could.. I would love to find my furever home where I can learn more and go on lots of adventures with my person!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Online Adoption Application 
Meet Max - this gorgeous boy came to the rescue a few months ago - scared & unsocialized, having lived mostly in a crate for the first few months of life. He got adopted, along with another of our PMR pups and at first did well. Not sure what happened but he got himself into some trouble with the neighbor and had to be returned. Max is a smart little guy and needs to burn off his energy and use his brain for good. It seems that introductions and interactions on leash are bothersome to him so that needs work and management. All people should learn to approach dogs appropriately and not all dogs want someone coming up while theya re stuck on a leash with their person, hovering over and sticking hands and fingers in the face. Max is a lovebug at his foster home with his human and has met others humans this week and is doing well. Introductions to dogs off leash have gone well. Seems like the leash really plays a role in his issues. Max is also working on his potty training - we think because of his crate confinement so early on, he just can't figure out that he should wait to go outside - when you gotta go, you gotta go - but he's improving and LOVES to get praise when he goes outside - he seems to think it's pretty neat! lol - Max is a smart boy needing an adopter ready to commit to him AND training. He loves toys and food and treats - he's been learning to use enrichment toys and thinks the KONG wobbler is pretty neat for dispensing his food. This handsome boy deserves the best - is that you?

animal.description:
This sweet boy is Cowboy.  He is a 2-3 year old Australian Cattle Dog mix who weighs 40 lbs.  Cowboy was found running around a rural neighborhood after being dumped so we do not know his backstory but we know he is loving, sweet, and good with other dogs. 

Cowboy loves to play!  He is an energetic dog (as many cattle dogs are).  He can be a little reserved meeting new people and dogs but once he warms up he is very loving.  Cowboy is good with other dogs.  He is at a daycare facility right now where he gets to play in group.  He seems to prefer female dogs.  

Cowboy would like a home where he is given lots of love and treated like a member of the family.  

Cowboy is not in a home but in a daycare facility so we are not sure if he is house trained.  He does keep his kennel clean.  He walks well on a leash.

Cowboy is neutered, microchipped, and current on his vaccines.  His adoption fee is $175.

If you would like to adopt Cowboy and make him a part of your family, please contact ForeverYoursOKC@gmail.com.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time.

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Hi, I'm Bo! I am the smartest dog at the Adoption Center! Yes, you read that right! I am an extremely bright dog and I have found myself in need of a home. Let me tell you about myself:

I am a handsome 4 year old retriever mix. I know a lot of tricks that I would love to show off to you. I am excellent at walking on leash and I love to go explore new places with my people. I am great at meeting new humans while out and about.

I love learning new things and then impressing people with my cool skills. When I'm tired out after walking or playing with my squeaky toys, I love to snuggle with my people. 

The coolest thing about me is my recall. I have been practicing my recall from very impressive distances. I can sit and stay and then come back to you on command, no matter how far away you are. I have mastered the entire distance of my yard here, but I would like to try even farther if I have the chance. 

I am looking for a home with adults who want to continue my training. I never want to stop learning new things! You don't need any other pets if you have me-- I am endless fun and adventure, just waiting for you to find me! If you are looking for the smartest dog around, please make a special VIP appointment during the week to come meet me! I can't wait to show you everything I've learned!

I am a part of the Go Fetch Program! My adoption fee is waived and I come with free bonus items when adopted!

Adoption Coordinator: Adoption Center Staff
Location: Adoption Center

INCLUDES spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program/

animal.description:
MEET JACKIE!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. She is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4503241.

Jackie was an owner surrender. She lived in the owner's yard with two other dogs and barked a lot. A neighbor reported the owners and they could not take Jackie into the home because of space issues. Jackie came into the shelter with her ribs, hip bones and spine showing. She is very fearful in the kennel, tries to escape from the play yard and is very wary of people. She is highly treat motivated. Jackie's behavior has improved in the shelter and she is no longer at risk of being euthanized. Despite her past she is showing amazing progress and just wants to be loved. Please remember Jackie was a backyard dog, so she still needs an experienced owner who will be patient with her and continue working on her training. If you're interested in meeting Jackie call the shelter today!

To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show. We have been told that you can go straight to the shelter and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog. From what we understand, the shelter will squeeze you in. (Please know this is not a guarantee). We hope your adoption process is smooth and full of happiness.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

animal.description:
Please note donations using the SPONSOR ME tab will not go to Fluffy Dog Rescue.

To Locate Our Application go to http://rescue.fluffydog.net/how-to-adopt.html

Our listings are updated throughout the day. If there is an applicant, it will say PENDING ADOPTION next to the dog's name. If not, please submit an Application that can be found on our site, www.fluffydog.net. 

MY AGE: approx. 20 week s (1/26)  WEIGHT: approx. 20 lbs. (1/19) WHERE I AM FROM: AL (arrival 11/28) 

MY STORY: Miss Jingle has been with us for about a month now and I really need to update her bio. She's just so perfect, I'm afraid that someone will see her new bio and scoop her up and I'm just not ready to send her along yet. However, furever family, I know you're out there just waiting for your perfect dog and here she is.

She has grown into the most beautiful girl.Her mangey coat has filled in nicely and she's shiny and gorgeous. She is getting better at sit and while it's hard, patience for treats and not bowling everybody over, is coming along. She gets along well with my all female pack but loves to chase and chew on the kitties. Her feet, which were once oddly flat, have popped up like they should. Not sure why they were flat but they are perfect now and she loves to run on them and tear around in the snow. She is very "hands on" and uses her paws like raccoon feet, if that makes sense.

During the day, she's a typical wild puppy but at night, at night she loves to snuggle and cuddle, as close as she can possibly get. 

She's started shedding her baby teeth but is not chewing on anything inappropriate. We have lots of bones and soft toys for her to work on those teeth. 

She's mostly housetrained. If I had to pick a number I'd say 85%, but maybe some of that is on us.

She's very smart and very gentle. If you're looking for a friend, Jingle is your girl. 

 This dog does shed and is not hypoallergenic.

HOUSEBROKEN?   GOOD WITH DOGS?  Yes  GOOD WITH CATS?unknown

ADOPTION FEE: $550

To adopt the FIRST STEP is to complete an APPLICATION. The application can be found on our site www.fluffydog.net, or by clicking on the purple Fluffy Dog Rescue wording found in the left corner of this page under the dogs name.

Our dogs are located in foster homes throughout the state. We do not have a facility. Adopters must be 24 years old.We can not adopt to families with children under the age of six. We also adopt in WI, IL, and parts of MN. Most of our dogs are strays, so the breed is our best guess.
WI License #270548.
 
Check out Fluffy Dog Wellness on our Home Page. Great Solutions to Enhance Your Pet's Health. www.fluffydog.net

animal.description:
"Hey there,

My name is Jacob, and I just joined the adoptable doggy crew at Providence Animal Center after traveling here from Georgia. I'm around 6 years old, about 50 pounds, and I'm all set to move right into your heart & home today - already neutered, microchipped & up to date on vaccinations. 

I’m a Siberian Husky through and through, with all the associated behaviors and personality! You know - loyal, intelligent, mischievous, the Houdini of the dog world, playful, high energy, athletic, free-spirited, good-natured. Experienced, diehard Husky lovers will know what I mean - and that’s actually the exact forever human I’m in search of. My ideal home will be adult-only (I play hard & love hard), probably where I’m the only dog, with a human who knows that I’ll keep them on their toes but wouldn’t have it any other way. 

As I mentioned the bit about Houdini, my home will also obviously have a super securely fenced yard, so I can’t find a way out when I’m in the mood for an extra adventurous day.

So, if you're that human I've described - who knows firsthand all about the fantastic quirks of my breed and the many benefits that come along with them when provided the physical & mental enrichment we thrive on - and you think I could be your new BFF, please email a completed adoption profile (found here - http://www.providenceac.org/adopt-a-pet/how-to-adopt/) to my good friend, Dayna (dvilla@providenceac.org), and she'll be in touch to set up an appointment with you to meet me.
I'm looking forward to it for sure!  XO Jacob

P.S. I almost forgot!  Someone is so excited for me to find my fur-ever home, that they have sponsored my adoption fee! That means I can join your family today for FREE! Woohoo!!"

_______
Providence Animal Center relies on adoption fees and donations to save pets! Adoption fees vary per pet. 

Can’t adopt? Consider fostering or donating! Visit https://providenceac.org/support-us/ for more information on how you can support the lifesaving mission!

animal.description:
Meet this charming fella named Romeo! He came into the shelter November 19, 2020 when his owner had landlord issues and was no longer able to keep Romeo. Very sad for them both. Romeo is 10 years old, current on shots, neutered, house broken, and owner said he does well with most all animals with proper introduction. He is super sweet and knows some commands like sit, shake, stay, down, speak, and will heel. He would love a home where someone is home most of the time if possible he does get anxious when left alone a d owner said he will pace the floor and howl. He just loves his human friends and misses them and hope they will hear his howl. All in all Romeo is a sweetheart so deserves to spend his “golden years” being pampered and loved in a cozy and loving FOREVER home. Maybe you have the most am amazing FOREVER home for handsome Romeo?! Visit with him today and adopt him into your heart and home!
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

animal.description: Ivan IS AVAILALBE (updated 02-02-2021).To meet any of our dogs you must first complete our online adoption application on our website. For more information and the adoption application for Ivan, please visit our website belowhttp://www.coastalgsr.org/dog_profile.php?ID=22254&name=IvanIvan has made so much progress since his rescue. At the shelter, he wouldnt come out of his run. He was freaked out when they tried to leash him up, frantically bolting to escape, gator rolling to avoid being handled, and refusing to be coaxed out of his run with food and even a puppy friend. He wasnt a candidate for public adoption, so a rescue became his only option.Ivan joined us in January of 2020. Step one was to get him comfortable with us and step two was to get him on a slip lead. We made slow but steady progress, but it was clear that everything was new and overwhelming to him. We worked on building confidence, trust, and obedience.After months, he was comfortable enough to go for a walk around the neighborhood. After another few months, we started getting him comfortable with getting in a car, which terrified him at first. He can now go on walks with volunteers and enjoys checking out the local message boards.Ivan has had a long road, but we think hes ready to join a family: a family who understands that he's still fearful of the unknown and hes going to need help and time to get used to their routine. A family who can show him structure, is patient, and knows that the time they put into working with Ivan will pay off ten fold. A family who can show Ivan there are people who consider dogs part of the family and dont just leave them outside until they decide to dump them at shelters. A family who will love him and get a loyal companion in return. The minimum adoption donation for adults is $375 and the adoption donation for puppies is $500. This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is tax deductible. The adoption donation provides that all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis ( i.e., puppies who will need to be altered by 6 mos old). Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description: Maxwell is the definition of tall, dark and handsome! Add inquisitive, obedient and loyal to the list, and he is the whole Shepherd package. He loves to be active with his people, whether playing fetch, going for walks or rides in the car. He seems to smile when he knows you are going to do something fun! Maxwell may seem to play hard-to-get when first meeting people, but he warms up once he knows you are a true friend who is up for going for a jog or cuddling on the couch. If you happen to be up for training and brain games, then Maxwell is your match. He already knows many commands, is eager to continue learning and loves treats! Given his height, he may try to stick his snoot in your treat pouch to sneak some snacks - he is such a funny boy! This sweet boy is looking for an adult-only home that will go at his pace when meeting new people, given his sense of loyalty. He wants to make sure he and his people are safe. While not playful, Maxwell does appreciate other dogs and could go home with one of similar size. Smaller dogs and kitties are enticing to him, so likely not the ideal housemates. Maxwell is house-trained and can be left free to roam in the house. Maxwell is ready for a home to call his own. Could it be yours? Come meet this funny boy!

animal.description: GOOBER is an 8 year old Terrier mix taken in on 11/13/20 when his owner was incarcerated. He was living inside a house without electricity or water. As you can see from his photos, Goober looks hairless. He has a severe yeast infection all over his skin and is now being treated to remedy it. The infection not only looks bad, but makes his skin feel very itchy, compelling Goober to want to spend a lot of time rolling on his back in the grass. His skin irritation is no laughing matter, but the high number of cycling reps Goober executes with his back legs is amusing. Following a lengthy roll in the grass, we were able to get some photos of this fantastic doggo. Goober has a great demeanor. Simply put, he's a real friendly, easy going dog. Goober's a great walker, super sweet and gets along with everyone: people, cats and dogs. He is housebroken. Goober's adoption fee is $75. He's altered, current on shots, wormed and treated with monthly flea and tick preventive. Goober was heart worm positive at intake and has been treated. He will need to complete filtration in February.

animal.description:
Wyatt is estimated to be about 3-4 years old and was found dragging a chain wrapped around tire.  He was not reclaimed from the shelter.  He is a sweet and friendly boy, who gets along well with other dogs, and loves all humans. He is a bit of a "houdini" dog, so will need a home with a 5' -6' fenced yard or a walk only home.  We do not adopt to homes with tie outs or trolleys. He loves human attention and  the companionship of other dogs.  He would do best in a home with another dog. He is fine with children,  He is a little too interested in cats to be trusted alone with them.    If you do not have 6' secure fencing, you must be an adult only home and committed to walking the dog. We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 5 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Wyatt will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a 6' securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $300

animal.description:
This big headed fella goes by the name Tucker!  Tucker joined us at the Canine Rescue after his dad fell ill and was unable to care for his boy anymore.   Tucker's dad was heartbroken to say goodbye to his best friend, but he knew he had to do what was best for him.  

Tucker is approximately 3 and a half years old and is a bit of a chunky fella.   The volunteers are working to get some weight off of him.   Tucker is also having some issues with his left ear.  The medical team is working with the vet on getting that cleared up.   Tucker is such a good boy, allowing the volunteers to put medicine in his ears twice a day.

Tucker walks well on a leash and is a kind of chill fella.  He enjoys car rides and snuggling under the blanket.  Tucker has been around kids before but he hasn't ever lived with little humans.   Due to this, we think he would be fine with older kiddos!   Tucker has also been around other pups before and done well, but he hasn't lived with any.  

If you are interested in meeting Tucker or fostering him while his ears heal, please go to our website, www.crcpa.org, and complete an application!

Breed: Pomeranian/Poodle Mix
Age: 10
Weight: 13Lbs
Good With Dogs: Must be an only dog
Good With Cats: Unknown
Good With Kids: Loves older children
Energy Level: Mostly calm but still playful

Needs And Special Considerations

Secure Fence Required: Yes
Another Dog In The Home: No
Experienced Adopter: Yes
Medical: No known conditions

Shadow was a “house dog” on a breeding farm and, as such, is fairly well adapted. He loves car rides, older children, and does tricks for treats. He’s a sweet, gentle boy who loves attention but he’s also a bit of free spirit who would happily dig an escape route to check out the world so he will need a home with a secure fence and a watchful eye. 
Though he gets along well with other dogs the majority of the time, he would be happiest as an only dog because he can be a bit lap protective.
Shadow is a happy, smart, cuddly guy who would love nothing more than to spend his whole day at his owner's side-- riding in cars, being carried around, eating treats, watching tv from the couch, and sleeping in a warm bed at night. 


This dog is currently being fostered in Rochester, NY and cannot travel prior to adoption. Meet and greets available in the surrounding area only. Visitors welcome.

PLEASE NOTE: Unless otherwise written, all of our puppy mill survivors will require a secure fenced yard, another small dog in the home, and an experienced owner. Dogs rescued from puppy mills will have started to learn but cannot be expected to be fully potty trained at time of adoption.


PLEASE READ ALL OF THE INFORMATION BELOW:


We currently adopt in the states of NY, NJ, Eastern PA, DE, and some areas in MD. We cannot accept applications from other states at this time.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our adoption application which you can find on our website at www.dutchcountryanimalrescue.org/adopt.html 

We will reply within one week if your application meets the criteria for this dog. 

Our adoption fees are on our application.

All of our rescues are spayed/neutered, up to date on rabies and DHPP, heartworm tested, treated for worms and fleas and most are microchipped.

We are not a shelter, we are 100% volunteer public charity. All of our dogs are in foster homes until they are adopted. Since we are not a shelter, we do not receive government funding. We are a public charity that relies solely on funds through our adoption fee, fundraisers, and private donations. Since we are 100% volunteer based, all funds collected go directly towards the rescue and vet costs of our dogs.

We take each rescue personally and spend a lot of effort trying to match the right dog to the right family. Thank you for considering one of our rescued dogs.

animal.description:
JEWEL is a gorgeous Brindle Lab / Plott Hound mix!  Approx 3 years old and 45 lbs and very gentle and loving!

Jewel and her baby Jude (also listed for adoption) were rescued by from death-row at the shelter a few months ago.  Their skin was covered in mange and sores, and they were missing lots of hair.  They were petrified of people, and afraid to even eat.  

After their medical conditions were healed, they went to a loving foster home with daily TLC.  They are still shy with strangers, but have come a long way!  You can see the spark in their eyes and pep in their step now! What a transformation! Hard to believe their before photos!   

A home is needed with dog experienced adults, no human kids (they are too active and make them nervous), a doggie friend, and a good secure yard to run and play in.

Jewel is about 3 years old and Jude is a little less than a year!  

It would be great if they could stay together!  But if not, they definitely need to be in a home with another dog. 

Looking for some new best friends?  Email info@redcollar.org ?

Adoption applications can be submitted on our website, redcollar.org.

Age - 3 years
Weight -  45 lbs 
Dogs - yes - Jewel would love a friend!
Cats - unknown
Kids - no, they are too active and make Jewel nervous
Vaccinated - yes

animal.description:
**ADOPTERS WILL BE REQUIRED TO DRIVE TO CHICAGO, POSSIBLY MORE THAN ONCE-- if you live too far, please do not inquiry as animals will not be shipped**

His Story

Jack Frost was brought into a family in 2010 as a Christmas gift, and now, almost 10-years later, he has been abandoned ahead of the 2020 holiday season. It’s been no doubt an incredibly upsetting experience for Jack Frost, as he had spent so long with his family, but when they welcomed another dog into the mix, Jack Frost and him did not get along, and so, he was surrendered to Famous Fido Rescue. He still has a lot of energy, and loves to play and jump around, but he does need a little guidance and would benefit greatly from some training. We’d love to find him a home where he could be spoiled in by calm family as an only dog. He does react out of fear at times, so we would not recommend him for a home with young children. But, he has a very sweet nature that will work with a patient guardian that wants to see him through for life.

animal.description:
**ADOPTERS WILL BE REQUIRED TO DRIVE TO CHICAGO, POSSIBLY MORE THAN ONCE-- if you live too far, please do not inquiry as animals will not be shipped**

Her Story

Uki had lived with her one guardian her whole life, until he suffered a heart attack that lead to ongoing issues, keeping him in hospital for over a month. In that time Uki was left in an apartment, with someone dropping by each day to feed her. Going without her person for so long has definitely lead to her feeling bouts of sadness and anxiety, and we know she will likely grieve for some time. She will need someone who is patient, calm and caring to help her feel at home again. She tends to seize up around larger dogs, but smaller, less active cats or dogs might be okay for her to share a home with. She loves people, and desperately craves attention and love.  Uki would do best in a home with no young children as she likes to take it easy and isn't a fan of fast / loud movements / actions.

animal.description:
A second chance for Fisher. MUST HAVE A FENCED YARD
When we met Fisher he was in a Shelter and as you can imagine was very popular. Being a chocolate purebred Labrador doesn't happen very often in those places. Found out that Fisher was purchased in a puppy store in Miami then dumped on the street of Naples Florida, just like this. No one came for him and we started to wonder why? Only Fisher can tell us what happen to him and how he end it up homeless. He is in good health and really needs a home. We are looking for a very active family who loves running, walking and do things. He would be best if he was an only dog in the house. He will need an experience handler. He is a sweetheart but likes to push the limit as well. He is now in training for the past 3 months in near Ocala and is doing great. A fenced yard is a must  and no condos or apartment. Of course he loves the water and swimming. Fisher is a really good dog who just need someone knowledgeable about the breed. if you are interested in meeting him please email us at pets@findahomegiveahome.com. Sorry we do not adopt to family with children. 
He is up to date on all of his vaccines, neutered and microchip. His adoption fee is $650.00

animal.description:
Please read Lanie's entire description before applying.

 Lanie was part of a litter born to a semi feral husky mix mom under a vacant house. A kind neighbor put out food, but Lanie and her littermates had no social interaction with people until they were finally trapped. Lanie was nearly a year old before she was trapped. After a few months in a boarding kennel situation with her sister Meg, Lanie and her brother Winston were moved into a private home, where they were exposed to all the usual sounds of a household with people, dogs and cats. At this point, neither Winston or Lanie would allow anyone to touch them.

As of January 2021, Lanie is still shy, but much less so than before. She will allow the people she knows and trusts to pet her, but she can still be reserved with people she does not know. She and her brother Winston started attending doggy day care two days a week in January for more socialization with new people and new dogs. She is already making great progress in becoming less shy in just a couple of weeks.

 Lanie loves to go on her daily walks. She is more adventurous on walks than her brother Winston is. She is becoming much more interested when she sees approaching people and other dogs walking by. She loves to go on new routes and explore more places. She does not mind walking in light rain or chilly temperatures.

 Lanie can get a bit excited about the cats, but not so much as her brother Winston. 

Lanie and Winston would love to be adopted together. They are best friends.

animal.description:
Biggie... A big, beautiful boy with a big history. Biggie spent the first 10 months of his life in a shelter environment. He was adopted, returned 2 days later (due to no fault of his own), and scheduled to be euthanized. Thankfully, an amazing rescue partner stepped in and spared Biggies life. Fast-forward to today: Biggie is now between 3-4 years old. He is likely a boxer/Great Dane mix, and he weighs just under 100lbs. He is a complex boy who needs a very specific home, but we are confident we can find him the most perfect forever! In general, Biggie is apprehensive of all new people, but in particular of men and deep voices. He needs a home environment with minimal visitors. And when there are visitors, he needs his own space and a family who will follow a specific protocol for his needs as outlined by the awesome trainers who have been working with him. He also needs a 6ft(+) fenced-in yard. Biggie is not a dog that needs (or necessarily wants) to take walks; the commotion and stimulation of the encounters experienced on walks are stressful for him. He would also do best in a home with no young children and no cats/small animals. Biggie has lived successfully with other dogs, but the other dog(s) in the home should be quieter, to be a calming force for Biggie. Biggie has also started on some anxiety meds and they have helped him tremendously! He is much happier and more carefree. He truly is such a sweet, sweet boy who just needs to find his people/person. Once he is comfortable with you, he will love you like none other! Biggie knows basic commands, is potty-trained and crate-trained, and does do best crated when home alone due to experiencing some slight separation anxiety when his humans are away. His favorite activities include just hanging out with his people and especially snuggling. We would desperately love to get Biggie out of boarding and into a foster/adoptive home. Please share his handsome face far and wide! 

 

If you are willing to foster Biggie, PLEASE reach out to us (via either private message or by submitting an application at https://newleashdogrescue.com)!

 

**Biggies $200 adoption fee includes his neuter, vaccinations, heartworm test, and microchip.

animal.description:
This handsome dude is Titus, and he is looking to bust out of boarding and into a foster/adoptive home of his own before the holidays! He is a 2 year old pittie mix who is still young and impressionable, and needs a person/family who will help him continue to build his confidence and learn how to simply be a dog. He tends to view the world as big and scary, so he needs a calm home, a family that will help him maneuver new experiences at his own pace, and who will continue to work on his training with our amazing trainers at Fun Fur Pets. Titus has learned so much from the crew at FFP, and they have also been able to pinpoint the type of home environment that will best help Titus succeed and thrive. He needs a fenced-in yard (his safe space where he can run, roam, and play), and children in the home should be ages 16+. He is such a fun and playful boy who has so much love to give! He especially loves his 4-legged playmates, playing fetch, and with his toys. He is kennel-trained and potty-trained. He does need to go to a home without cats. More than anything, we would love to get Titus into a home (whether foster or adoptive) of his own, so if you can help this boy PLEASE reach out to us! 

If you are interested in fostering/adopting Titus, please either private message us or (if not already completed) fill out a general application at https://newleashdogrescue.com.

animal.description:
Introducing GUS (known to SAAP as Sosa).

I met this stunning 7 year old boy just yesterday ... and apparently he though i was someone else as he came bounding out to my car like we were long lost friends and planted kisses on my face when i leaned over to accept his hugs. I felt honored to have earned the trust and friendship of this boy so quickly. But then, after taking him around town . . . I realized it wasn't just me! He hasn't met a stranger. If you look at him or say hello, you're his new best friend and you're gonna get a hug, some butt wiggles, a bit of a dance and if your face is close...you're gonna get your face cleaned with a couple quick licks from his giant tongue.

When he arrived at my home he was fearful of my open stairs...but he took it slow and cautious for the first time, then he got braver and braver with each trip up. And just like that, he learned it was all ok.

Within minutes of arriving, i showed him where his "toy trunk" was and tossed a few toys out to see how he would react. He loves toys and he loves tug of war. . . but he doesn't destroy them, he just plays.

GUS loves to be close. . .he follows me from room to room and sits at my feet (in the office), curls up next to me on the couch and snuggles up close in bed. He is a great sleeper, and has all kinds of different "snores" that I wish I could interpret.

He is listed as an "only child" because at some point in his last home he got into a scuffle with another dog that wanted to have the same toy at the same time. So while he hasn't shown any aggression to any dog he has met on our walks or visits to daycare, something happened at some point to spark this new behavior so that's to be noted.

Today we went to the photo studio to get his glam shots and he was a champ, he took direction well and seemed very confident. He may have been a celebrity earlier in his life, or in a past life as the firing strobes from this puparazzi didn't give him pause.

So that's what i've learned in my first 24 hours about GUS (aka as Sosa on the SAAP website).

Oh, I almost forgot, so far, I haven't heard a bark. His snore has been the loudest thing so far.

P.S. THANK YOU to Allie's Walkabout for donating food for this guy while he is in this foster home.All SAAP animals are vet checked, UTD on vaccines, spayed/neutered, micro chipped, and given flea and heartworm preventative as age appropriate.

Our website is: http://www.adoptastray.com/

To check if this animal is still available visit our master pet list on our website at:
http://www.adoptastray.com/adoptable-animals/

Have questions:
Please email us at saap@adoptastray.com for more information about this animal or to answer any questions you may have. You may also contact us at (859)391-1234.

Completing the online application when you find an animal you are interested in speeds up the adoption process. We can hold your application on file for a period of time if you are still looking for that perfect new family member.

THE APPLICATION IS AVAILABLE AT THIS LINK:
http://www.adoptastray.com/dog-adoption-application/

INTERESTED IN FOSTERING:
We welcome your interest and ask that you complete our on-line foster application:
http://www.adoptastray.com/foster-application/

animal.description:
Please read Winston's entire description before applying.

 Winston was part of a litter born to a semi feral husky mix mom under a vacant house. A kind neighbor put out food, but Winston and his littermates had no social interaction with people until they were finally trapped. Winston was about 15 months old when he was trapped. After a few months in a boarding kennel situation, Winston and his sister Lanie were moved into a private home, where they were exposed to all the usual sounds of a household with people, dogs and cats. At that point, neither Winston or Lanie would allow anyone to touch them.

As of January 2021, Winston is much less shy, but he can still be hesitant around people he does not know. Once he knows and trusts you, he will be happy to have lots of pets and head massages.  Winston is an affectionate boy,  and he loves to kiss your face in return. Sometimes he gets a bit too rambunctious, and his nose can hit your face harder than you expect.  

 Winston and his sister Lanie started to attend doggy day care twice a week in January 2021 for more socialization with new people and new dogs. He is doing well, and has become a bit less shy after just a couple of weeks. 

  This playful boy likes to chew on bones and play with toys and other dogs. He can deftly pick up toys and other items (shoes, socks, etc.) without breaking his stride. He likes to shake and toss these items until he is asked to give them back. 

He loves to go on walks, and after the initial excitement wears off, he rarely pulls much on his leash. New routes and new places to walk still make him nervous, but he does love to go on his regular walk in his own neighborhood and along the nearby creek.

 Winston does not mind walking in light rain or chilly conditions.

 Winston has NEVER bit or snapped at any person, even when he was first brought into a home and he was scared to death of everything.

He has been exposed to cats in the house, but sometimes he has shown a desire to corner them. At this point, I am not sure it would be a good idea to have him in a house with cats, unless there was always human supervision.

 Winston is crate trained, and has not shown any tendency to get on the furniture.

 Winston and Lanie would love to be adopted together. They are best friends.

animal.description: One look into Augustus' big brown eyes and you'll be hypnotized! This boy will definitely steal your heart with his sweetness and silly antics. Since Augustus is deaf, he asks that his adopters be patient with him, as he is still working on learning hand signals. That's ok, he's smart and he's picking it up quickly. Augustus loves people but would benefit from being the only pet in the home. There are some great advantages to adopting a deaf dog. They aren't noise sensitive, so they won't be bothered by things like fireworks, construction sounds, or thunderstorms. They also won't hear you sneaking into the kitchen for a midnight snack. But on a more serious note, learning to train a deaf dog can vastly improve your dog handling skills and is often no more challenging than training a hearing dog! If you are interested in adorable Augustus, please complete a dog adoption survey at la.bestfriends.org/adopt for a team member to reach out to you.

Jax is a 4 year old bully mix about 74 pounds. He's lived around kids of all ages and does well with other dogs but we would want a home with a female no other males at this time. He's not good with cats. He was owner surrendered due to them not being able to keep him in their apartment. He's house and kennel trained and knows basic commands but will need his new family to keep up the training. 
He is currently in Fort Worth, TX but can make the trek to Olympia, WA scheduled to arrive on Saturday Dec 5th with a pre-adoption which is the only way to secure that he will for sure go home with you! Pre-Adoption means getting your app in, approved and paying the adoption fee to secure the ride.  His adoption fee is $395 which covers his neuter, vaccinations, HW testing, chipping, health certificate and transport fees. She had 10 puppies and was an incredible mom while she raised them for 12 weeks, but now it's time to find her forever home. She is sweet, loving, playful, and all around... an incredible friend. She would make a wonderful addition to any family.

Marsha is dog selective. She would do best with one-two calm dogs, or a patient person that can SLOWLY integrate her over the course of several days. She just needs a little stability before meeting higher energy doggos.

animal.description:
Meet Hope!

She is a 15 month old mixed breed, around 50lbs.

Hope is house and crate trained.

She is spayed, microchipped, current on annual vaccines and heartworm negative.

Has never showed any aggression (food, toy, people, animal or otherwise)

She is High energy, passionately playful, loving and a dedicated loyal companion.

Hope is having her knee surgery 1/18/2021 and will be recovering but is available for a foster to adopt home.

Hope is on the lookout for someone that would love a dog that LOVES your presence, your lap, your petting and love and attention. She loves to be with people and part of the fun!

The ideal home would include a fenced yard or an area that she can safely run and play with another dog or owner.

Hope still has puppy behavior but she listens and is very "trainable" and has learned to sit, "paw", lay down and working on "stay" and "come". She's smart and aims to please!

ADOPT HOPE!!!!

The adoption fee is $250.00 and we require a vet reference and home visit.
